# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battle-of-hampton-roads
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 8, 1864, near the end of the American Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President Abraham Lincoln of the National Union Party easily defeated the Democratic nominee, former General George B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, by a wide margin of 212–21 in the electoral college, with 55% of the popular vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For the election, the Republican Party and some Democrats created the National Union Party, especially to attract War Democrats.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite some intra-party opposition from Salmon Chase and the Radical Republicans, Lincoln won his party's nomination at the 1864 National Union National Convention.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Rather than re-nominate Vice President Hannibal Hamlin, the convention selected Andrew Johnson of Tennessee, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats were divided between the Copperheads, who favored immediate peace with the Confederacy, and War Democrats, who supported the war.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 Democratic National Convention nominated McClellan, a War Democrat, but adopted a platform advocating peace with the Confederacy, which McClellan rejected, although his running mate George H.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] While the Confederacy seemed to have survival potential in summer 1864, it was visibly collapsing by election day in November.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his early fears of defeat, Lincoln won strong majorities in the popular and electoral vote, partly as a result of the recent Union victory at the Battle of Atlanta.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War was still raging, no electoral votes were counted from any of the eleven southern states that had joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's re-election ensured that he would preside over the successful conclusion of the Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln's victory made him the first president to win re-election since Andrew Jackson in 1832, as well as the first Northern president to ever win re-election.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was assassinated six weeks into his second term.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was succeeded by his vice president, Andrew Johnson, who favored quick restoration of the seceded states to the Union without protection for the former slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This led to conflict with the Republican-dominated Congress, culminating in Johnson's impeachment by the House of Representatives in 1868; he was acquitted in the Senate by one vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election took place during the American Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] According to the Miller Center for the study of the presidency, the election was noteworthy for occurring at all, an unprecedented democratic exercise in the midst of a civil war.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Republican dissidents who called themselves Radical Republicans formed a party named the Radical Democratic Party and nominated John C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont as their candidate for president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont later withdrew and endorsed Lincoln.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] War Democrats joined with Republicans as the National Union Party, with Lincoln at the head of the ticket.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The National Union Party was a temporary name used to attract War Democrats and Southern Border State Unionists who would not vote for the Republican Party.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It faced off against the regular Democratic Party, including Peace Democrats.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 presidential election conventions of the parties are considered below in order of the party's popular vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] As the Civil War progressed, political opinions within the Republican Party began to diverge.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Senators Charles Sumner and Henry Wilson from Massachusetts wanted the Republican Party to advocate constitutional amendments to prohibit slavery and guarantee racial equality before the law.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, not all northern Republicans supported such measures.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic leaders hoped that the radical Republicans would put forth their own ticket in the election.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* newspaper, particularly interested in undermining the National Union Party, ran a series of articles predicting a delay for the National Union Convention until late in 1864 to allow Frémont time to collect delegates to win the nomination.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont supporters in New York City established a newspaper called the *New Nation*, which declared in one of its initial issues that the National Union Convention would be a "nonentity".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The *New York World* also published false information (further purported by Samuel S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Before the election, some War Democrats joined the Republicans to form the National Union Party.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With the outcome of the Civil War still in doubt, some political leaders, including Salmon P.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase, Benjamin Wade, and Horace Greeley, opposed Lincoln's re-nomination on the grounds that he could not win.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Chase himself became the only candidate to contest Lincoln's re-nomination actively, but he withdrew in March when a slew of Republican officials, including some within the state of Ohio upon whom Chase's campaign depended, endorsed Lincoln for re-nomination.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was still popular with most members of the Republican Party, and the National Union Party nominated him for a second term as president at their convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on June 7–8, 1864.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent vice president Hannibal Hamlin remaining indifferent about the prospect of a second term in office, Andrew Johnson, the former senator from and current military governor of Tennessee, was named as Lincoln's vice presidential running-mate.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He had been governor of Tennessee from 1853 to 1857 and was elected by the legislature to the Senate in 1857.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his congressional service, he sought passage of the Homestead Bill which was enacted soon after he left his Senate seat in 1862.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern slave states, including Tennessee, seceded, he remained firmly with the Union.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] He was the only sitting senator from a Confederate state who did not resign his seat upon learning of his state's secession.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1862, Lincoln appointed him as military governor of Tennessee after most of it had been retaken.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In 1864, Johnson was a logical choice as running mate for Lincoln, who wished to send a message of national unity in his re-election campaign, especially to ensure the electoral votes of the border states.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Others who were considered for the nomination, at one point or another, were former Senator Daniel Dickinson, Major General Benjamin Butler, Major General William Rosecrans, Joseph Holt, and former Treasury Secretary and Senator John Dix.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party was bitterly split between War Democrats and Peace Democrats, a group further divided among competing factions.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Moderate Peace Democrats who supported the war against the Confederacy, such as Horatio Seymour, were preaching the wisdom of a negotiated peace.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After the Union victory at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, moderate Peace Democrats proposed a negotiated peace that would secure Union victory.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They believed this was the best course of action, because an armistice could finish the war without devastating the South.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Radical Peace Democrats known as Copperheads, such as Thomas H.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Seymour, declared the war to be a failure and favored an immediate end to hostilities without securing Union victory.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan vied for the presidential nomination.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, friends of Horatio Seymour insisted on placing his name before the convention, which was held in Chicago, Illinois, on August 29–31, 1864.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] But on the day before the organization of that body, Horatio Seymour announced positively that he would not be a candidate.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Since the Democrats were divided by issues of war and peace, they sought a strong candidate who could unify the party.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The compromise was to nominate pro-war General George B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan for president and anti-war Representative George H.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan, a War Democrat, was nominated for president over the Copperhead Thomas H.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Pendleton, a close associate of the Copperhead Clement Vallandigham, balanced the ticket, since he was known for having strongly opposed the Union war effort.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention adopted a peace platform – a platform McClellan personally rejected.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan supported the continuation of the war and restoration of the Union, but the party platform, written by Vallandigham, opposed this position.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The Radical Democratic Convention assembled in Ohio with delegates arriving on May 29, 1864.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] *The New York Times* reported that the hall which the convention organizers had planned to use had been double-booked by an opera troupe.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Almost all delegates were instructed to support Frémont, with a major exception being the New York delegation, which was composed of War Democrats who supported Ulysses S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Various estimates of the number of delegates were reported in the press; *The New York Times* reported 156 delegates, but the number generally reported elsewhere was 350 delegates.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates came from 15 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They adopted the name Radical Democratic Party.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] A supporter of Grant was appointed chairman.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The platform was passed with little discussion, and a series of resolutions that bogged down the convention proceedings were voted down decisively.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The convention nominated Frémont for president, and he accepted the nomination on June 4, 1864.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his letter, he stated that he would step aside if the National Union Convention would nominate someone other than Lincoln for president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] John Cochrane was nominated for vice president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The 1864 election was the first time since 1812 that a presidential election took place during a war.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] For much of 1864, Lincoln himself believed he had little chance of being re-elected.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Confederate forces had triumphed at the Battle of Mansfield, the Battle of Cold Harbor, the Battle of Brices Cross Roads, the Battle of Kennesaw Mountain and the Battle of the Crater.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the war was continuing to take a very high toll in terms of casualties with campaigns such as Grant's Overland Campaign and the perceived lack of progress.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of a long and bloody war started to make the idea of "peace at all cost" offered by the Ultra Peace Democrats look more desirable.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] However, several political and military events eventually made Lincoln's re-election inevitable.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the first place, the Democrats had to confront the severe internal strains within their party at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The political compromises made at the Democratic National Convention were contradictory and made McClellan's efforts to campaign seem inconsistent.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Secondly, the Democratic National Convention influenced Frémont's campaign.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Frémont was appalled at the Democratic platform, which he described as "union with slavery".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] After three weeks of discussions with Cochrane and his supporters, Frémont withdrew from the race in September 1864.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In his statement, Frémont declared that winning the Civil War was too important to divide the Republican vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Although he still felt that Lincoln was not going far enough, the defeat of McClellan was of the greatest necessity.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] General Cochrane, who was a War Democrat, agreed and withdrew with Frémont.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, 1864, Frémont also brokered a political deal in which Lincoln removed U.S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Postmaster General Montgomery Blair from office, and on September 24 Abraham Lincoln relieved Blair of his duty as Postmaster General.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan's chances of victory faded after Frémont withdrew from the presidential race.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lastly, with the fall of Atlanta on September 2, there was no longer any question that a Union military victory was inevitable and close at hand.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, the Union Party mobilized the full strength of both the Republicans and the War Democrats under the slogan "Don't change horses in the middle of a stream".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] It was energized as Lincoln made emancipation the central issue, and state Republican parties stressed the perfidy of the Copperheads.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] 24.4% of the voting age population and 76.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The American Civil War was in progress and unfinished during this election.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Because eleven Southern states plus two claimed additional Southern states had declared secession from the Union and formed the Confederate States of America, only twenty-five states participated in the election.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Louisiana and Tennessee had recently been re-captured.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] They chose presidential electors, but their votes were rejected by Congress due to having recently seceded from the Union.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Both states had voted for Lincoln, so it would not have changed the result in any case.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Three new states participated for the first time: Kansas, West Virginia, and Nevada.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] McClellan won just three states: Kentucky, Delaware, and his home state of New Jersey.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln won in every state he carried in 1860 except New Jersey, and also carried a state won four years earlier by Stephen Douglas (Missouri), one carried by John C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge (Maryland) and all three newly admitted states (Kansas, Nevada and West Virginia).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Altogether, 212 electoral votes were counted in Congress for Lincoln – more than enough to win the presidency even if all of the states in rebellion had participated and voted against him.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This would be the last election in which a party nominee won completely different states than the previous nominee, with McClellan flipping Kentucky and New Jersey, while having lost Missouri.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Lincoln was highly popular with soldiers and they in turn recommended him to their families back home.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] The following states allowed soldiers to cast ballots: California, Kansas, Kentucky, Maine, Michigan, Rhode Island, and Wisconsin.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Only soldiers from Kentucky gave McClellan a majority of their votes, and he carried the army vote in the state by a vote of 2,823 (70.3%) to 1,194 (29.7%).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,129 counties making returns, Lincoln won in 728 (64.5%), while McClellan carried 400 (35.4%).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] One county (0.1%) in Iowa split evenly between Lincoln and McClellan.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election the Republicans won in Maryland until 1896.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] (a) *The states in rebellion did not participate in the election of 1864.* (b) *The 17 electoral votes from Tennessee and Louisiana were rejected.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1864-united-states-presidential-election] States in red were won by Republican Abraham Lincoln; states in blue were won by Democrat George B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation was launched before the adjournment of the trial and continued after the trial adjourned on May 26, 1868.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The leading figure of the investigation was Benjamin Butler.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The final report of the investigation was published on July 3, 1868.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On February 21, 1868, in disregard for the Tenure of Office Act, Andrew Johnson (the president of the United States) attempted to replace Edwin Stanton (the United States secretary of war) with Lorenzo Thomas.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This led the United States House of Representatives, on February 24, to impeach Johnson.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After the impeachment, an impeachment trial began in the United States Senate where the Senate would judge whether to convict Johnson, thereby removing him from office.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While the investigation never proved bribery, there is evidence of efforts by both those supporting the prosecution and the defense having made offers to senators to persuade their votes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This includes evidence of promises of patronage jobs, cash bribes, and political dealmaking being made to solicit votes for acquittal.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There is evidence that the prosecution may have attempted to bribe the senators voting for acquittal to switch their votes to conviction.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Aspects of this possible scheme were partially uncovered by the investigation, but it was never proven by the investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] All of the individuals, except for Wooley, had ties to United States Secretary of State William H.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Seward, who also appears implicated in this scheme.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Evidence also suggests that Alexander Randall and Edmund Cooper (a leader at the United States Department of the Treasury) were possibly in charge of managing an "acquittal fund" for Johnson.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On May 16, 1868, the Senate voted against convicting Johnson on the eleventh article of impeachment, which had been considered the article with the strongest chance of securing a conviction.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It fell one vote shy of the two-thirds needed for impeachment, with the vote to convict being 32–21.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After this, the Senate voted to adjourn the trial and reconvene to resume voting on the remaining ten articles of impeachment on March 26, 1868.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This resolution had been justified by the impeachment managers with the claim that information had been provided to them that provided them with probable cause to suspect improper or corrupt means had influenced the Senate vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After the resolution passed, a subcommittee was created and began hearing testimony during the hiatus.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation that subsequently unfolded proved relatively extreme and unconstrained.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The leading force of the investigation was Benjamin Butler (R– MA).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers, during the hiatus between votes, began searching for possible corrupt means that may have persuaded senators to acquit.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation took a heavy-handed prosecutorial approach, subpoenaing telegrams, and looking into the bank accounts of private citizens that just-so happened to have withdrawn large amounts.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler was confident that votes had been bought by Johnson allies, and wanted to prove it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The effort was disparaged as a "smelling committee" by Democrats and some of the press.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Many Republicans were also dubious towards the investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While there is substantial evidence to suggest that there were several senators that voted to convict who Johnson could likely have counted on to vote for an acquittal had their votes been needed, only those who actually voted to convict were the focus of the impeachment managers' investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the telegrams found were a number that seemed incriminating.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Hours before the vote on May 16 to acquit, Charles Woolley sent Congressman George H.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pendleton (D– OH) a telegram reading, "Andy all right." Many witnesses testified that they had heard talk of vote-purchasing, but many of these witnesses were also unable to recall who they heard it from or greater details about what they had heard.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Within hours of the authorization of the investigation, the impeachment managers had subpoenaed eight witnesses, including Senator Edmund G.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross (who had voted to acquit), Perry Fuller (an Indian trader and a political fixer), and several individuals from Missouri that had tried unsuccessfully to convince John B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] That evening, the committee began hearing testimony, with their first witness being Senator Ross' brother William, who expressed disappointment in his brother's vote but denied any knowledge of corruption in the Senate vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers received a large number of tips from people around the country of leads they should pursue.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, the individual who had Butler's ear the most with his advice on this was *National Police Gazette*-publisher George Wilkes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes' newspaper was known to scandalmonger.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes had a secret informant that was close to Samuel Ward (a notable lobbyist).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This source reported that Ward had paid Senator Edmund G.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross for his vote to acquit with $12,000 from Democratic congressman John Morrissey.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wilkes speculated that the transfer of money was handled by "Charley Morgan", who was a cross-dresser who was allegedly involved in separate extramarital affairs with both Morrissey's wife and Samuel Ward.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During the middle of the investigation, a young woman going by the name "Charley Morgan" was arrested in New York, pleading guilty to a misdemeanor charge of "indecency" for crossdressing.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] She told the court that she had gone four years without wearing women's clothing.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler, however, gave assurances to Ward that this was not his doing, pointing to the fact that he had gone against pressure to embarrass Ward by calling her as a witness in the investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler would never find proof that Ward had bribed Ross.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation included a focus on a number of Johnson-allied figures, including Thurlow Weed and Charles Woolley.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Thurlow Weed told the committee that there had been a group that was determined to secure Johnson's acquittal.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Smythe was an individual that had been accused of corruption in the past, and had previously nearly been ejected from office as a result.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Weed also said that it included Sheridan Shook, former congressman Samuel S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During the investigation, there was evidence found that United States Secretary of State William Seward and Postmaster General Alexander Randall had been in contact with Cornelius Wendell (a Washington printer) for the purposes of organizing bribes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wendell told the committee that he had been uninterested in being part of this plan, and pointed blame on Seward's aide Erastus Webster, who it appeared had collected a fund of $165,000 for the purposes of buying acquittal votes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This money was said to have primarily been raised by Randall, Hugh McCulloch (United States secretary of the treasury) and Henry A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Smythe through middlemen such as Perry Fuller and James Legate (a special agent of the Kansas Post Office Department), though Fuller and Legate were said to have pocketed most of the money raised for themselves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Wendell also testified about Charles Woolley's alleged involvement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] James Legate testified that Perry Fuller had told him that, if impeachment failed, Salmon Chase (the chief Justice of the United States, who acted as the trial's presiding officer) would run a third-party campaign for the presidency.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He also said that the raising of money for a potential Chase presidential bid was being used as a front for establishing a fund to support the acquittal of Johnson.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the other individuals interviewed was Thomas Ewing Jr.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Much evidence implicated Senator Samuel C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pomeroy, who had voted to convict, in possible corruption.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler attempted to ignore this evidence, however.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation uncovered evidence that there had been discussions of bribes for votes to convict.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was discovered during the investigation that Kansas Senator Pomeroy, who voted for conviction, had written a letter to Johnson's postmaster general seeking a $40,000 bribe for Pomeroy's acquittal vote along with three or four others in his caucus.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley became a central focus of Butler's from the first day of the trial.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers sought to hear from Woolley, who kept giving changing excuses for inability to come before them.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Among the matters they had questions for Woolley about was $10,000 that he had received from Sheridan Shook, a deputy collector of internal revenue in New York.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley had withdrawn the money in $1,000 bills, which drew suspicion.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] When he appeared himself, Shook answered very few questions in his testimony before the committee, and many of his answers were seen as nonsensical.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Other witnesses on this matter had feigned ignorance or had been otherwise evasive in their answers to questions.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ordway (the sergeant at arms of the House) took custody of Woolley and brought him before the House on March 26.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, Woolley's appearance was interrupted that day by a recess so that congressmen could attend the Senate impeachment trial vote that day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The committee submitted a report on their preliminary findings on May 26, hours before the Senate met again to vote on articles of impeachment.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] While some senators attempted to get the trial to adjourn until the end of June to allow the impeachment managers more time to investigate before the vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This was rejected because few others believed that the allegations could be proven.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The Senate voted identically on the second and third articles of impeachment, again by 32–21 votes before voting to adjourn sine die.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On March 26, 1868, after the trial adjourned, the House voted 91–30 to approve a resolution presented by Benjamin Butler authorizing the House impeachment managers to continue this investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler led the continuation of the investigation and conducted hearings and inquiry into widespread reports that Republican senators had been bribed to vote for Johnson's acquittal.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] On March 26, shortly after the Senate trial adjourned, the impeachment managers returned to question Charles Woolley.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He failed to cooperate with their questioning, refusing to answer questions that he asserted were unrelated to the trial.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] This included questions about what he had done with $10,000 that he had received from a deputy collector of internal revenue in New York named Sheridan Shook.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After this, House voted 60–51 that day to hold him in contempt of Congress and had him held in custody by the sergeant at arms of the House.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He was first kept in the House Committee on Foreign Affairs' hearing room, but, as his arrest grew in length, he was later moved to the basement room that Vinnie Ream had been utilizing as a sculpture studio, forcing the artist to move her work into the hallway.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Conservatives charged that Benjamin Butler was intentionally targeting Ream in his successful resolution to turn her studio into a Capitol Police guardroom.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Woolley's arrest attracted great media attention.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] When Woolley was questioned on May 27, he was denied a request for a lawyer.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler found him still inadequately responsive to questions, and sent him back to his holding cell.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The final report Butler wrote doubted this, calling it a, "stupid fabrication".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Eleven days later, Woolley told that house he would answer Butler's questions, and Butler questioned him again.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Van Valkenberg came before the committee again, with $17,000 of cash and accompanied by a hotel manager who told the impeachment managers that this money had indeed been in a hotel safe.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was impossible to prove whether this was Woolley's money or not.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] After he appeared before the investigative committee and answered their questions to an extent that they found satisfactory, the House voted to discharge Woolley from their custody on June 11, 1868.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The impeachment managers took testimony for a total of six weeks the May 16 authorization of their investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In some instances, Butler individually interrogated witnesses.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] During these six weeks, Butler had detectives search for proof of bribery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There was some speculation that Butler was motivated by a desire to not be blamed himself for the failure to secure a conviction.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was rumored, however, that Butler hidden thirty-six volumes of incriminating telegrams in hopes he could later use them to blackmail congressional colleagues in the future.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was also rumored that Butler had offered $100,000 to Cornelius Wendell in exchange for information, but had suppressed evidence of this offer.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In the post-trial hearings and investigations there was growing evidence that some acquittal votes were acquired by promises of patronage jobs and cash bribes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Grimes received assurances that acquittal would not be followed by presidential reprisals; Johnson agreed to enforce the Reconstruction Acts, and to appoint General John Schofield to succeed Stanton.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Nonetheless, the investigations never resulted in charges, much less convictions, against anyone.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] The investigation also boomeranged by uncovering evidence that there had been discussions of bribes for vote to covict.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Democrats were not worried by the investigation, and came to see it as amusing due to Butler's failure to find hard evidence of bribery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It was reported that the impeachment managers had testimony showing implications of bribery, but did not provide solid evidence of bribery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In contrast the strictness that Woolley had faced, the impeachment managers were more lax when it came to the testimony of some witnesses.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] A number of witnesses were allowed to decline to answer questions, be evasive, or contradict evidence without consequence.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Some witnesses faced informal questioning that was not under oath.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Samuel Ward smoked cigars with Butler after he testified before the committee for two hours.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Adams, being questioned for allegedly originating a bribery scheme, gave what the impeachment managers found to be an "utterly false and untruthful" claim by declaring he could not recall at what time he had become a general, Butler did not pursue any action against him.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler, perhaps, was selective with what truths he sought to uncover in the investigation, hoping only to find those that would harm the president and the Democratic Party and help the Republicans.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Even when it came to matters he wanted to uncover, Butler appears to have been selective in which leads he chose to follow, disregarding some leads more that were potentially promising than the ones he chose to follow.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Fowler as having been bribed for his vote against impeachment.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Seven congressmen gave a statement that, in January 1868, Fowler had demanded the impeachment of Johnson.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Henderson, who had promised to vote to convict on the eleventh article four days before he voted to acquit on it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] There is historical evidence that Perry Fuller had bribed Senator Ross.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] However, Butler never managed to prove this act of bribery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Fuller admitted that, at the authority of Edmund Cooper, he had offered $40,000 to Senator Samuel C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Pomeroy's brother-in-law Willis Gaylord.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] In late-May 1868, amid the investigation, he acknowledged having paid for the outstanding expense of the home mortgage of James Legate.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] It appears that Legate had also given Fuller his records of the bribery scheme, and that Fuller had burned them.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Historical evidence shows that Fuller had admitted to doing so in hopes of, "drying up the investigation".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Being unable to definitively prove that bribery took place, Butler wrote a final report on the evidence found and testimony taken by the impeachment managers in their investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Butler rushedly published the final report of the investigation on July 3, 1868.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He hoped that this would hurt Johnson's prospects at the Democratic Party's presidential nomination at the 1868 Democratic National Convention held in New York City the following week.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Senators suspected of selling their acquittal votes attacked the report on the Senate floor.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Ross attacked what he called Butler's, "well-known groveling instincts and proness to slime and uncleanness".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Eighteen months after the end of the trial, journalist Henry V.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Boynton published an investigative news report that sought to tie up loose ends in Butler's investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He identified three different alleged bribery schemes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Boynton was unhappy with Butler's handling of the impeachment managers' investigation, believing his pursuit of Woolley had been to the detriment of pursuing other guilty parties.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] He was also angered by Butler's failure to publish important testimony from the investigation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Cornelius Wendell gave a news interview that confirmed aspects of Boynton's reporting, and which accused Perry Fuller of offering Senator Ross several thousand dollars to influence his vote.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1868-impeachment-managers-investigation] Few transcripts of testimony from the investigation survive.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The **1913 Gettysburg reunion** was a Gettysburg Battlefield encampment of American Civil War veterans for the Battle of Gettysburg's 50th anniversary.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The June 29 – July 4 gathering of 53,407 veterans (about 8,750 Confederate) was the largest Civil War veteran reunion.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] All honorably-discharged veterans in the Grand Army of the Republic and the United Confederate Veterans were invited, and veterans from 46 of the 48 states attended (all except Nevada and Wyoming).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Despite official concerns "that there might be unpleasant differences, at least, between the blue and gray" (as after England's War of the Roses and the French Revolution), the peaceful reunion was characterized by instances of Union–Confederate camaraderie.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] After a number of smaller Gettysburg reunions, including the 1906 Philadelphia Brigade-Pickett's Division reunion during which Brigadier General Lewis Armistead's captured sword was returned to the South, in April 1908 General Henry S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Huidekoper of Philadelphia suggested a 1913 50th anniversary reunion to Pennsylvania Governor Edwin Sydney Stuart.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On September 8, the Gettysburg National Park Commission met with Gettysburg borough officials about the event.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Stuart held a sub-committee meeting on October 25, and addressed the General Assembly about the matter in January 1909.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On May 13, 1909, the Pennsylvania Assembly created the Fiftieth Anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg Commission.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission's "first tentative programme" of October 13, 1910 included a "Peace Jubilee", with a noon July 3 placement of the cornerstone for a "Great Peace Memorial".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The August 26, 1912, US Congress bill appropriated $150,000 and directed the War Department to establish the camp.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Because the memorial funding was not approved, the Peace Jubilee plans were removed from the schedule.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The site of the camp and the 8 acres (3.2 ha) for the Great Tent, west of the Codori House, were selected in 1912 and mapped by the Gettysburg National Park Commission.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission also painted avenue fencing, gun carriages, iron tablets, pyramids, and shells from 1912 through June 30, 1913.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On April 13, 1913, the Pennsylvania commission completed the Pennsylvania State Memorial and mailed invitations to 40,000 veterans.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On June 28, President Woodrow Wilson notified the Pennsylvania commission that he would attend the reunion for a "very limited period".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The 33 contributing states provided a total of $1,033,000 for the reunion, with $450,000 coming from Pennsylvania.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania commission headquarters at Gettysburg was at 231 Baltimore Street, with the Harrisburg office of the Secretary (later nicknamed the "Duke of Gettysburg") in Pennsylvania State Capitol's Room 509.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Commemorative tokens and programs were designed for attendees, including three types of Pennsylvania badges ("Press", "Guest", and "Scout"), a commemorative medal, and a souvenir program of poems by attending "Veteran Scout" Jack Crawford.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania Railroad added "a telephone line between Gettysburg and Hanover along the Western Maryland Railway, over which the Pennsy [would] operate a large number of trains during the battle anniversary".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On the Chambersburg-Gettysburg turnpike and the Gettysburg-Petersburg turnpike, tolls ended for the reunion.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania Supreme Court upheld the 1911 Sproul Roads Act on June 27, enabling the Commonwealth to acquire private toll roads and make them free for the public.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Water wells were being drilled for the July encampment by February 1, 1913, and hotels in Hanover, Chambersburg, Hagerstown, and "the Blue Ridge section [were] filling rapidly" by June 26.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The War Department's Great Camp (Gettysburg Encampment, Anniversary Camp, or Veterans Camp) provided tents and support facilities for the Civil War veterans and extended from both sides of Long Lane on the north to within 500 yd (460 m) of the Bliss House.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Post Office; 90 Pennsylvania Health Department latrines throughout the camp, with a seating capacity of 3,476; and (near the Great Tent) an emergency station and two health-department Comfort Houses which supplied the Great Tent water fountains.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Pennsylvania commission set up a temporary morgue in the camp.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A special platform on the Round Top Branch was built for veterans to disembark from steam trains into the camp; in February, trolleys of the Gettysburg Electric Railway had been prohibited from using the branch.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The department set up a field hospital on the Kurtz property facing Brickyard Lane on the north foot of East Cemetery Hill and six comfort stations in the borough: one at each railroad station.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The department tested borough wells and mitigated contamination sources upstream from the water-works supply on Marsh Creek.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The American Red Cross Society and 72 additional Boy Scouts operated fourteen 7 ft × 7 ft (2.1 m × 2.1 m) relief stations for first aid and rest on the battlefield-park roads.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Gettysburg's Tuberculosis Dispensary was also used as a relief station.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Attached to the Great Camp were a battery of the Third United States Field Artillery and several companies of regular infantry.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Companies A-D (14 officers and 285 men) of the Fifteenth United States Cavalry arrived on June 26 to guard the battlefield, camping west of Seminary Ridge on the Hagerstown Road.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A "model Camp" for a Pennsylvania cavalry squadron was on the "College Athletic Field" adjoining the commission's headquarters.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A total of 527 people were quartered at the Lutheran Theological Seminary at Gettysburg and Pennsylvania College (renamed Gettysburg College in 1921), including the Pennsylvania Gettysburg Commission, four troops of the Pennsylvania State Police, and (in tents) Governor Tener's staff.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The commission planned a four-day series of events, with each day dedicated to a different group.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Anticipating that some veterans might arrive early (especially those traveling a long distance), the Great Camp was opened for supper on June 29.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Pennsylvania veterans who attended the state reunion, which adjourned on June 28, made up most of the over 21,000 arrivals that day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Other veterans arriving early included two Confederate veterans of Culp's Hill, who arrived on June 26.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Captain McCaskey of the Quartermasters Corps had estimated that 6,000 men might arrive on June 29, and temporarily struggled with shortages of food and supplies.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Some veterans left without staying another night.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] On June 30, the 1912 base of the Virginia Monument was dedicated; the rest of the monument was completed later.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] At night, a "Union raid" on the Confederate side of the Great Camp was followed by joint parades and campfires.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] ; eight senators, and 21 congressmen were among the officials who arrived that day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] at 9 p.m. included "gigantic set pieces covering the entire face and crest of Little Round Top".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] ; eight statues had been installed in April.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Woodrow Wilson arrived at 11 a.m. in a special rail car, traveled through the borough, and entered the Great Tent through two rows of Boy Scouts.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] He addressed the audience in the Big Tent about national unity, and left the camp after the National Anthem was played.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] At noon, a five-minute tribute was held in silence for "Our Heroic Dead"; people throughout the area stood at attention, including at the "College Hotel" and "Seminary Hotel".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The tribute began with a bugle salute while the Gettysburg bells in the distance tolled.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The remaining minutes of silence were punctuated by periodic artillery firing in the distance.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] From 5 a.m. to 11 p.m., 7,147 automobiles used the national-park roads as visitors departed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] About 12,000 veterans had already left on July 2, and about the same number on July 3.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] During the evening of July 2 at the Hotel Gettysburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Henry (a Southerner living in Philadelphia) uttered a "vile epithet" about President Abraham Lincoln and caused an argument at his table.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A Union man threw his drink at Henry, who stabbed and slashed men at the table and on his way out to the street before he was apprehended.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The Virginia governor spoke to officials on behalf of Henry, and his father (a Confederate major) posted bail for his son.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The victims (all but one of whom were taken to a hospital) were all expected to recover, and most were released from the hospital the next day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Dismantling of the Great Camp began immediately after the July 4 tribute.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The hospital closed on July 5, and the last veteran left on July 8.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The annual military instructional camp (250 college students) used several tents in the veterans' camp at the "Meadeboro" camp (Newspaper Row) from July 7 to August 15.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] The quartermaster headquarters on Baltimore Street closed on August 13, and by August 15 the Grand Camp had been removed except for "four great water storage reservoirs".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] A film, *United at Gettysburg*, documented the reunion and was shown at local theaters.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] Beitler, Secretary of the Commission, finished compiling the organizations' reports on December 31, 1913.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1913-gettysburg-reunion] To commemorate the reunion, a colonial portico was opened in May 1914 at the seminary's Old Dorm; only the concrete base remains.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The **1938 Gettysburg reunion** was an encampment of American Civil War veterans on the Gettysburg Battlefield for the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The gathering included approximately 25 veterans of the battle with a further 1,359 Federal and 486 Confederate attendees out of the 8,000 living veterans of the war.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Transportation, quarters, and subsistence was federally funded for each veteran and their accompanying attendant.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] If an attendant was needed it was provided.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Roosevelt's July 3 reunion address preceded the unveiling of the Eternal Light Peace Memorial; a newsreel with part of the address was included in the Westinghouse Time Capsule for the 1939 New York World's Fair.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The reunion's support personnel included 19 officers and 250 enlisted men of the Pennsylvania National Guard, and there were 3,185 United States Army personnel in total.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] A "regular army camp" that displayed modern weapons was east of the northward tracks of the Reading Railroad to the Gettysburg College buildings, while the Third Corps headquarters tent was south of Gettysburg near The Angle.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] There were 548 police; from the Pennsylvania State Police and officers from New York City, Philadelphia, and Pittsburgh; and a Gettysburg College building was the "base hospital" under the First Regular Army Medical Regiment.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] To raise reunion funds, in June 1936 Congress authorized 50,000 US Mint commemorative half dollars.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] The Battle of Gettysburg half dollar was dated 1936 despite being struck in 1937.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Sculptor Frank Vittor had used Union veteran James Power Stanley of the Battles of the Wilderness, Cold Harbor, North Anna, and Spotsylvania for the model, A special US postage stamp was also advocated for the reunion's opening day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] hours was between the reviewing stand in the college stadium and the intersection of the Baltimore Pike and the Emmitsburg Road, through the Lincoln Square; and included three groups: distinguished visitors first, followed by U.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] Army units and equipment, and more than 50 drum and bugle corps.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] concert was held in the Gettysburg College stadium (the only remaining Jewish Civil War veteran, Daniel Harris, was a guest on the platform).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/1938-gettysburg-reunion] at dusk, and searchlights were directed from the ground at the planes while they dropped flares.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-lincoln-portrait] Conductor Andre Kostelanetz commissioned Copland to write a musical portrait of an "eminent American" for the New York Philharmonic.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-lincoln-portrait] Copland chose President Abraham Lincoln, and used material from speeches and letters of Lincoln, as well as original folk songs of the period, including "Camptown Races" and "On Springfield Mountain." Copland finished *Lincoln Portrait* in April 1942.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-lincoln-portrait] The Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra premiered the work on May 14, 1942, with William Adams as the narrator.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-lincoln-portrait] Because of his leftist views, Copland was blacklisted and *Lincoln Portrait* withdrawn from the 1953 inaugural concert for Dwight D.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-lincoln-portrait] Aaron Copland had come to Caracas to conduct the first Venezuelan performance of *Lincoln Portrait* on March 27, 1957.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-lincoln-portrait] A *New York Times* reviewer said it had a "magical impact" on the audience.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] A Virginian, Hill was a career United States Army officer who had fought in the Mexican–American War and Seminole Wars before joining the Confederate States Army.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] After the start of the American Civil War, he gained early fame as the commander of the "Light Division" in the Seven Days Battles.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He became one of Stonewall Jackson's ablest subordinates, distinguishing himself in the 1862 battles of Cedar Mountain, Second Bull Run, Antietam, and Fredericksburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Following Jackson's death in May 1863 at the Battle of Chancellorsville, Hill was promoted to lieutenant general and commanded the Third Corps of Robert E.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Lee's Army of Northern Virginia, which he led in the summer Gettysburg campaign and the fall campaigns of 1863.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] His command of the corps in 1864–65 was interrupted on multiple occasions by illness, from which he did not return until just before the end of the war.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He was killed during the Union army's offensive at the Third Battle of Petersburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill, known to his family as *Powell* (and to his soldiers as *Little Powell*), was born in Culpeper, Virginia, the seventh and final child of Thomas and Fannie Russell Baptist Hill.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Powell was named for his uncle, Ambrose Powell Hill (1785–1858), who served in both houses of the Virginia legislature, and Capt.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Ambrose Powell, an Indian fighter, explorer, sheriff, legislator, and close friend of President James Madison.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The younger Powell Hill lived with his family in a home on North Main Street in Culpeper as a child from age four or age seven.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill was nominated to enter the United States Military Academy in 1842 in a class that started with 85 cadets.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He made friends easily, including such prominent future generals as Darius N.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Reno, George Stoneman, Truman Seymour, Cadmus M.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] "Stonewall" Jackson, was in the same class, but the two did not get along.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill had a higher social status in Virginia and valued having a good time in his off-hours.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In contrast, Jackson scorned levity and practiced his religion more fervently than Hill could tolerate.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In 1844, Hill returned from a furlough with a case of gonorrhea, causing medical complications that caused him to miss so many classes that he had to repeat his third year.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Reassigned to the class of 1847, he made new friendships, in particular with Henry Heth and Ambrose Burnside.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill continued to suffer from the effects of the STI for the rest of his life, being plagued with recurrent prostatitis, which was not treatable before the advent of antibiotics.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He may have also suffered urinary incontinence due to inflammation of the prostate pressing on his urethra, which could also lead to uremic poisoning and kidney damage.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He graduated in 1847, ranking 15th of 38.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Artillery as a brevet second lieutenant.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He served in a cavalry company during the final months of the Mexican–American War but fought in no major battles.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] After some garrison assignments along the Atlantic seaboard, he served in the Seminole Wars, again arriving near the war's end and fighting various minor skirmishes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He was promoted to first lieutenant in September 1851.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Robertson's biography of Hill quotes his wife Kitty as saying her husband "never owned slaves and never approved of the institution of slavery." His family, however, was involved with the institution.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In the 1850 census, Thomas Hill (Hill's father) enslaved 20 people in Culpeper County.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Ten years later, Thomas Hill Jr. enslaved at least 38 people in Culpeper County.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill, for whom he was named, was also a major planter in Culpeper County, Virginia, based on using enslaved labor.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In the 1840 census, the senior Ambrose P.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill enslaved 32 people, 30 people in the 1850 census, and 10 in 1860.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill worked for the United States Coast Survey.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Marcy before her parents pressured her to break off the engagement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] She married Hill's West Point roommate George B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] McClellan, who later was Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Although Hill denied he felt ill will afterward, during the war, a rumor spread that Hill always fought harder if he knew McClellan was present with the opposing army because of Ellen's earlier rejection.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] On July 18, 1859, Hill married Kitty ("Dolly") Morgan McClung, a young widow.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He became the brother-in-law of future Confederate cavalry generals John Hunt Morgan (Hill's best man at the wedding) and Basil W.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] On March 1, 1861, after some slave states had declared secession from the United States, and as the Virginia Secession Convention of 1861 met, Hill resigned his United States Army commission.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The 13th Virginia was one of the regiments in Brig.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Johnston's army that was transported by the railroad as reinforcements to the First Battle of Bull Run, but Hill and his men were sent to guard the Confederate right flank near Manassas and saw no action during the battle.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill was promoted to brigadier general on February 26, 1862, and commanded a brigade in the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In the Peninsula Campaign of 1862, Hill performed well as a brigade commander at the Battle of Williamsburg, where his brigade blunted a U.S. attack, and was promoted to major general and division command on May 26.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's new division was composed mainly of brigades pulled from the Carolinas and Georgia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] His division did not participate in the Battle of Seven Pines (May 31 – June 1), the battle in which Joseph E.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Johnston was wounded and replaced in command of the Army of Northern Virginia by Robert E.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] June 1 was the first day Hill began using a nickname for his division: the *Light Division*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] This contradictory name for the largest division in all Confederate armies may have been selected because Hill wished his men a reputation for speed and agility.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's rookie division was in the thick of the fighting during the Seven Days Battles, being heavily engaged at Mechanicsville, Gaines Mill, and Glendale.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Following the campaign, Hill became involved in a dispute with James Longstreet over a series of newspaper articles that appeared in the *Richmond Examiner*; relations between them deteriorated to the point that Hill was placed under arrest and Hill challenged Longstreet to a duel.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Following the Seven Days Battles, Lee reorganized the army into two corps and assigned Hill's division to Stonewall Jackson.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Their relationship was less than amicable, and the two quarreled many times.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill frequently found himself under arrest by Jackson.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] At the Battle of Cedar Mountain on August 9, Hill launched a counterattack that stabilized the Confederate left flank, preventing it from being routed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Three weeks later, at the Second Battle of Bull Run (Second Manassas), Hill was placed on the Confederate left along the unfinished railroad cut and held it against repeated U.S. attacks.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the campaign, Hill became involved in several minor disputes with Jackson concerning Jackson's marching orders to Hill.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's performance at the Battle of Antietam was particularly noteworthy.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] While Lee's army was enduring strong attacks by the U.S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Army of the Potomac outside Sharpsburg, Maryland, Hill's Light Division had been left behind to process U.S. prisoners of war at Harpers Ferry.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Responding to an urgent call for assistance from Lee, Hill marched his men at a grueling pace and reached the battlefield just in time to counterattack a strong forward movement by the corps of Maj.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Ambrose Burnside, which threatened to destroy Lee's right flank.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's arrival neutralized the threat, ending the battle with Lee's army battered but undefeated.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hours after the battle, Hill told an inquisitive major that Burnside owed him $8,000.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the retreat back to Virginia, he had his division push back a few regiments from the U.S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] George Meade's division routed two of Hill's brigades and part of a third.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Early's division to repulse the U.S. attack.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's division suffered over 2,000 casualties during the battle, which was nearly two-thirds of the casualties in Jackson's corps; two of his brigade commanders were wounded, one (Maxcy Gregg) mortally.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] After the battle, one of his brigade commanders, Brig.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Archer, criticized him for the gap left in the division's front line, saying that Hill had been warned about it before the battle but had done nothing to correct it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill was also absent from his division, and there is no record of where he was during the battle; this led to a rumor spread through the lines that he had been captured during the initial U.S. assault.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill and Jackson argued several times during the Northern Virginia Campaign and 1862 Maryland Campaign.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the invasion of Maryland, Jackson had Hill arrested and charged him with eight counts of dereliction of duty after the campaign.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the lull in campaigning following the Battle of Fredericksburg, Hill repeatedly requested that Lee set up a court of inquiry.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Still, the commanding general did not wish to lose his two experienced lieutenants' effective teamwork, so he refused to approve Hill's request.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Their feud was put aside whenever a battle was being fought and then resumed afterward, a practice that lasted until the Battle of Chancellorsville in May 1863.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] There, Jackson was accidentally wounded by the 18th North Carolina Infantry of Hill's division.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill briefly took command of the Second Corps and was wounded himself in the calves of his legs.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] While in the infirmary, he requested that the cavalry commander, J.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] One of Hill's divisions, led by his West Point classmate Maj.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Henry Heth, was the first to engage Union soldiers at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Although the first day of the battle was a resounding Confederate success, Hill received much postbellum criticism from proponents of the Lost Cause movement, suggesting that he had unwisely brought on a general engagement against orders before Lee's army was fully concentrated.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Anderson fought in the unsuccessful second day assaults against Cemetery Ridge, while his favorite division commander, Maj.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] William Dorsey Pender, commanding the Light Division, was severely wounded, which prevented that division from cooperating with the assault.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] On the third day, two-thirds of the men in Pickett's Charge were from Hill's corps, but Robert E.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Lee chose James Longstreet to be the overall commander of the assault.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Of all three infantry corps of the Army of Northern Virginia, Hill's suffered the most casualties at Gettysburg, which prompted Lee to order them to lead the retreat from Gettysburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the Bristoe Campaign of the same year, Hill launched his Corps "too hastily" in the Battle of Bristoe Station and was bloodily repulsed by Maj.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Lee did not criticize him for this afterward but ordered him to detail himself to the dead and wounded after hearing his account.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's corps also participated in the Battle of Mine Run.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Other than a brief visit to Richmond in January 1864, Hill remained with his corps in its winter encampments near Orange Court House.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In the Overland Campaign of 1864, Hill's corps held back multiple U.S. attacks during the first day of the Battle of the Wilderness but became severely disorganized as a result.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Despite several requests from his division commanders, Hill refused to straighten and strengthen his line during the night, possibly due to Lee's plan to relieve them at daylight.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] At dawn on the second day of the battle, the Union army launched an attack that briefly drove Hill's corps back, with several units routed, but the First Corps under Longstreet arrived just in time to reinforce him.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill was medically incapacitated with an unspecified illness at the Battle of Spotsylvania Court House, so Maj.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Jubal Early temporarily took command of the Third Corps.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Still, Hill could hear that his men were doing well and observed the battle at Lee's side.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] After recovering and regaining his corps, he was later rebuked by Lee for his piecemeal attacks at the Battle of North Anna.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] By then, Lee was too ill to coordinate his subordinates in springing a planned trap against Union forces.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill held the Confederate left flank at Cold Harbor, but two divisions of his corps were used to defend against the main U.S. attack on the right flank on June 3; when part of the troops to his right gave way, Hill used one brigade to launch a successful counterattack.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the Siege of Petersburg of 1864–65, Hill and his men participated in several battles during the various U.S. offensives, particularly Jerusalem Plank Road, the Crater, Globe Tavern, Second Ream's Station, and Peebles' Farm.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the Battle of the Crater, he fought against his West Point classmate Ambrose Burnside, whom the former repulsed at Antietam and Fredericksburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] After the Battle of the Crater, Hill paraded 1,500 Union prisoners through Petersburg, where they were mocked by racist onlookers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill was ill several times that winter; in March 1865, his health had deteriorated to the point where he had to recuperate in Richmond until April 1, 1865.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill had said he had no desire to live to see the collapse of the Confederacy.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] On April 2, 1865 (during the U.S. breakthrough in the Third Battle of Petersburg, just seven days before Lee's surrender at the Battle of Appomattox Court House), he was shot dead by a Union soldier, Corporal John W.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Mauk of the 138th Pennsylvania Infantry, as he rode to the front of the Petersburg lines, accompanied by one staff officer.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill had attempted to induce the Union soldiers to surrender.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Instead, the Union soldiers refused and shot Hill through the chest.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The rifle bullet traveled through his heart, exited his chest, and sliced off his left thumb.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill fell to the ground and died within moments.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In the late nineteenth century, interest developed in trying to locate and memorialize the site where Hill was killed, with apparent attempts made to locate the site in 1888, 1890, and 1903.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] It was not until 1911, however, that the Sons of Confederate Veterans undertook a careful study and located where Hill fell.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In April 1912, the SCV unveiled two monuments denoting the death of A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The larger of these two monuments is located at the Boydton Plank Road and Duncan Road intersection.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He was killed about 600 yards northwardly from this marker, being shot by a small band of stragglers from the Federal lines on the morning of April 2, 1865.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] This location was thought to be chosen because it was easily accessible from the road.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] A small parking area is located behind the monument on Duncan Road, making it easy and safe to visit and access.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The SCV also marked what was thought in April 1912 to be the exact site where Hill fell.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] It is approximately a half mile from the larger stone.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The marker is located near Sentry Hill Court and is on land that the American Battlefield Trust preserved.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] It is publicly accessible via a short trail.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's widow and his surviving children attended the unveiling ceremony for the two markers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Across the Boydton Plank Road (US 1) from the "Memory" marker is a third marker to A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The Conservation & Development Commission erected this marker in 1929.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In the field a short distance north of this road, the Confederate General A.P.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill, not knowing that Lee's lines had been broken, rode into a party of Union soldiers advancing on Petersburg.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The marker was replaced as recently as 2015.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] It is located just south of the turn-off for the marker in the Sentry Hill area.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] There is no designated pull-off area for this marker.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Confederates recovered Hill's corpse shortly afterward.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Per his will, Hill was interred standing up.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill did not escape controversy during the war.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He had a frail physique and suffered from frequent illnesses that reduced his effectiveness at Gettysburg, the Wilderness, and Spotsylvania Court House.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Some analysts consider Hill an example of the Peter principle.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Although he was extremely successful commanding his famed "Light Division," he was less effective as a corps commander.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Historian Larry Tagg described Hill as "always emotional ... so high strung before battle that he had an increasing tendency to become unwell when the fighting was about to commence." This tendency was, to some extent, balanced by the implied combative attitude that he displayed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] He often donned a red calico hunting shirt when a battle was about to start, and the men under his command would pass the word, "Little Powell's got on his battle shirt!" and begin to check their weapons.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill was affectionate with the rank-and-file soldiers, and one officer called him "the most lovable of all Lee's generals." Although it was said that "his manner [was] so courteous as almost to lack decision," his actions were often impetuous and did not lack decision, but judgment.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Nevertheless, Hill was one of the war's most highly regarded generals on either side.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In 1897, the Sons of Confederate Veterans (SCV) in Petersburg held its first meeting and decided to name its camp after A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill because he defended the city, his Third Corps included Petersburg's own 12th Virginia Infantry regiment, and because Gen.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill died in nearby Dinwiddie County during the Third Battle of Petersburg a few days before General Lee surrendered the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] They also erected a marker where Hill fell mortally wounded.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Prominent commanders of the camp (lodge) included Congressman Patrick Henry Drewry and Petersburg's multi-term state senator Samuel D.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The camp may have lapsed after 1938 but was revived on June 9, 1959, with David Lyon as its Commander.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Petersburg also named a school after Hill and others for Lee, Stonewall Jackson, and J.E.B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's sword is on display at the Chesterfield County Museum in Chesterfield, Virginia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's remains were reinterred twice in Richmond.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In February 1867, Hill's remains were reinterred in Richmond's Hollywood Cemetery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During the late 1880s, several former comrades raised funds for a monument to Hill in Richmond.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's remains were again transferred, to the base of a monument dedicated on May 30, 1892, on land donated by developer Lewis Ginter.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] General Henry Heth led the procession to the dedication, and General James A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] A bronze statue of Hill, created by Caspar Buberl after William Ludwell Sheppard's design, topped the monument, while its plaster cast was given to the A.P.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The monument was located in the center of the intersection of Laburnum Avenue and Hermitage Road in what is now the city's Hermitage Road Historic District.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] This monument was the only one of its type in Richmond under which the subject individual was interred.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] On June 26, 2020, the Hermitage Road Historic District Association released a public statement requesting that the City of Richmond remove and relocate the monument to a more appropriate location.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] This request occurred within the context of the contemporary Black Lives Matter movement, and further impetus for the removal of Confederate monuments had been provided by protests in Richmond and elsewhere that followed the murder of George Floyd by a Minneapolis police officer in May 2020.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In January 2022, the administration of Richmond mayor Levar Stoney announced that the Richmond statue and remains of Hill would be removed soon.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The City of Richmond gained authority to remove monuments to war veterans on public city grounds from legislation signed into law by Virginia Governor Ralph Northam on April 11, 2020.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Because Hill was the only Confederate general who was buried under his monument in Richmond, government officials delayed any tampering with the monument until they could find a final resting place for Hill's remains.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Following the filing of a lawsuit by members of A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's extended family of descendants, who claimed that they, and not the City of Richmond, had the right to determine the disposition of the statue, a Virginia circuit court ruled in favor of the city's plan to transfer the statue to the Black History Museum and Cultural Center of Virginia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The statue was removed on December 12, 2022, after the denial of a motion by the extended family members to stay its removal.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] It was the last statue of a Confederate officer standing in Richmond.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill, which were exhumed one day later on December 13, were expected to be reinterred in a cemetery in Culpeper, Virginia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill was buried in Fairview Cemetery in Culpeper, Virginia, on January 21, 2023.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The statue will remain in storage until an appeal by A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill's descendants is resolved, who want the statue to be relocated to Cedar Mountain Battlefield for it to continue to serve as Hill's grave marker.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] The United States military named both a fort and a ship after Hill.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Hill (1941–2023), is located in Caroline County, Virginia, about halfway between Richmond and Washington, D.C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] During World War II, the United States Navy named a liberty ship the SS *A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In 2020, there were calls to rename U.S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Army installations named after Confederate soldiers, including Fort A.P.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] In September 2022, Secretary of Defense Lloyd J.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Austin III accepted the Naming Commission's recommendation to rename Fort A.P.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Army surgeon, Civil War prisoner of war, and Medal of Honor recipient Mary Edwards Walker.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/a-p-hill] Fort Walker received its new name in a ceremony on August 25, 2023.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery movement originated during the Age of Enlightenment, focused on ending the transatlantic slave trade.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In Colonial America, a few German Quakers issued the 1688 Germantown Quaker Petition Against Slavery, which marked the beginning of the American abolitionist movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the Revolutionary War, evangelical colonists were the primary advocates for the opposition to slavery and the slave trade, doing so on the basis of humanitarian ethics.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, others such as James Oglethorpe, the founder of the colony of Georgia, also retained political motivations for the removal of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Prohibiting slavery through the 1735 Georgia Experiment in part to prevent Spanish partnership with Georgia's runaway slaves, Oglethorpe eventually revoked the act in 1750 after the Spanish's defeat in the Battle of Bloody Marsh eight years prior.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] During the Revolutionary era, all states abolished the international slave trade, but South Carolina reversed its decision.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between the Revolutionary War and 1804, laws, constitutions, or court decisions in each of the Northern states provided for the gradual or immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No Southern state adopted similar policies.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1807, Congress made the importation of slaves a crime, effective January 1, 1808, which was as soon as Article I, section 9 of the Constitution allowed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A small but dedicated group, under leaders such as William Lloyd Garrison and Frederick Douglass, agitated for abolition in the mid-19th century.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown became an advocate and militia leader in attempting to end slavery by force of arms.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Civil War, immediate emancipation became a war goal for the Union in 1863 and was fully achieved in 1865.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism began well before the United States was founded as a nation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1652, Rhode Island made it illegal for any person, black or white, to be "bound" longer than ten years.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The law, however, was widely ignored, and Rhode Island became involved in the slave trade in 1700.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] An early prominent example of resistance by enslaved people occurred during Bacon's Rebellion in 1676.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Occurring in Virginia, the rebellion saw European indentured servants and African people (of indentured, enslaved, and free negroes) band together against William Berkeley because of his refusal to fully remove Native American tribes in the region.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the time, Native Americans in the region were hosting raids against lower-class settlers encroaching on their land after the Third Powhatan War (1644–1646), which left many white and black indentured servants and slaves without a sense of protection from their government.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Led by Nathaniel Bacon, the unification that occurred between the white lower class and blacks during this rebellion was perceived as dangerous and thus was quashed with the implementation of the Virginia Slave Codes of 1705.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Still, this event introduced the premise that blacks and whites could work together towards the goal of self-liberation, which became increasingly prevalent as abolition gained traction within America.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first written statement against slavery in Colonial America was prepared in 1688 by members of the Religious Society of Friends.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The intention of the petition was to stop slavery within the Quaker community, where 70% of Quakers owned slaves between 1681 and 1705.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It acknowledged the universal rights of all people.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the Quaker establishment did not take action at that time, the unusually early, clear, and forceful argument in the petition initiated the spirit that finally led to the end of slavery in the Society of Friends (1776) and in the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania (1780).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Quaker Quarterly Meeting of Chester, Pennsylvania, made its first protest in 1711.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Within a few decades the entire slave trade was under attack, being opposed by such Quaker leaders as William Burling, Benjamin Lay, Ralph Sandiford, William Southby, John Woolman, and Anthony Benezet.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benezet was particularly influential, inspiring a later generation of notable anti-slavery activists, including Granville Sharp, John Wesley, Thomas Clarkson, Olaudah Equiano, Benjamin Franklin, Benjamin Rush, Absalom Jones, and Bishop Richard Allen, among others.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Samuel Sewall, a prominent Bostonian, wrote *The Selling of Joseph* (1700) in protest of the widening practice of outright slavery as opposed to indentured servitude in the colonies.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This is the earliest-recorded anti-slavery tract published in the future United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery was banned in the colony of Georgia soon after its founding in 1733.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The colony's founder, James Edward Oglethorpe, fended off repeated attempts by South Carolina merchants and land speculators to introduce slavery into the colony.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His motivations included tactical defense against Spanish collusion with runaway slaves, and prevention of Georgia's largely reformed criminal population from replicating South Carolina's planter class structure.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1737, Quaker abolitionist Benjamin Lay published *All Slave-Keepers That Keep the Innocent in Bondage, Apostates*, which was printed by his friend, Benjamin Franklin.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The event resulted in 25 colonists and 35 to 50 African slaves killed, as well as the implementation of the 1740 Negro Act to prevent another slave uprising.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In her book, "The Slave's Cause" by Manisha Sinha, Sinha considers the Stono Rebellion to be an important act of abolition from the perspective of the slave, recognizing their agency and subsequent humanity as cause for self-liberation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The struggle between Georgia and South Carolina led to the first debates in Parliament over the issue of slavery, occurring between 1740 and 1742.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Rhode Island Quakers, associated with Moses Brown, were among the first in America to free slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Benjamin Rush was another leader, as were many Quakers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Woolman gave up most of his business in 1756 to devote himself to campaigning against slavery along with other Quakers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Between 1764 and 1774, seventeen enslaved African Americans appeared before the Massachusetts courts in freedom suits, spurred on the decision made in the *Somerset v.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Stewart* case, which although not applying the colonies was still received positively by American abolitionists.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Boston lawyer Benjamin Kent represented them.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whipple*) to liberate Jenny Slew, a mixed-race woman who had been kidnapped in Massachusetts and then handled as a slave.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian Steven Pincus, many of the colonial legislatures worked to enact laws that would limit slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Provincial legislature of Massachusetts Bay, as noted by historian Gary B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nash, approved a law "prohibiting the importation and purchase of slaves by any Massachusetts citizen." The Loyalist governor of Massachusetts, Thomas Hutchinson, vetoed the law, an action that prompted angered reaction from the general public.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionists were cheered by the decision in *Somerset v Stewart* (1772), which prohibited slavery in the United Kingdom, though not in its colonies.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1774, the influential Fairfax Resolves called for an end to the "wicked, cruel and unnatural" Atlantic slave trade.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One of the first articles advocating the emancipation of slaves and the abolition of slavery was written by Thomas Paine.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Titled "African Slavery in America", it appeared on 8 March 1775 in the *Postscript to the Pennsylvania Journal and Weekly Advertiser*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage (Pennsylvania Abolition Society) was the first American abolition society, formed 14 April 1775, in Philadelphia, primarily by Quakers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The society suspended operations during the American Revolutionary War and was reorganized in 1784, with Benjamin Franklin as its first president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1777, the Vermont Republic became the first independent state in North America to prohibit slavery: slaves were not directly freed, but masters were required to remove slaves from Vermont.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Constitution included several provisions which accommodated slavery, although none used the word.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Passed unanimously by the Congress of the Confederation in 1787, the Northwest Ordinance forbade slavery in the Northwest Territory, a vast area (the future Ohio, Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, and Wisconsin) in which slavery had been legal, but population was sparse.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to begin a gradual abolition of slavery was Pennsylvania, in 1780.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All importation of slaves was prohibited, but none were freed at first, only the slaves of masters who failed to register them with the state, along with the "future children" of enslaved mothers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Those enslaved in Pennsylvania before the 1780 law went into effect were not freed until 1847.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Massachusetts took a much more radical position.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1780, during the Revolution, Massachusetts ratified its constitution and included within it a clause that declared all men equal.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Based upon this clause, several freedom suits were filed by enslaved African Americans living in Massachusetts.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1783, its Supreme Court, in the case of *Commonwealth v.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nathaniel Jennison*, reaffirmed the case of *Brom and Bett v.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Ashley*, which held that even slaves were people who had a constitutional right to liberty.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This gave freedom to slaves, effectively abolishing slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] States with a greater economic interest in slaves, such as New York and New Jersey, passed gradual emancipation laws.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While some of these laws were gradual, these states enacted the first abolition laws in the entire "New World".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the State of New York, the enslaved population was transformed into indentured servants before being granted full emancipation in 1827.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In other states, abolitionist legislation provided freedom only for the children of the enslaved.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In New Jersey, slavery was not fully prohibited until the passage of the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All of the other states north of Maryland began gradual abolition of slavery between 1781 and 1804, based on the Pennsylvania model and by 1804, all the Northern states had passed laws to gradually or immediately abolish it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slaves continued in involuntary, unpaid "indentured servitude" for two more decades, and others were moved south and sold to new owners in slave states.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some individual slaveholders, particularly in the upper South, freed slaves, sometimes in their wills.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many noted they had been moved by the revolutionary ideals of the equality of men.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The number of free blacks as a proportion of the black population in the upper South increased from less than 1 percent to nearly 10 percent between 1790 and 1810 as a result of these actions.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some slave owners, concerned about the increase in free blacks, which they viewed as destabilizing, freed slaves on condition that they emigrate to Africa.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] All U.S. states abolished the transatlantic slave trade by 1798.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] South Carolina, which had abolished the slave trade in 1787, reversed that decision in 1803.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the American South, freedom suits were rejected by the courts, which held that the rights in the state constitutions did not apply to African Americans.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The institution of slavery remained solid in the South, and that region's customs and social beliefs evolved into a strident defense of slavery in response to the rise of a growing anti-slavery stance in the North.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1835 alone, abolitionists mailed over a million pieces of anti-slavery literature to the South, giving rise to the gag rules in Congress, after the theft of mail from the Charleston, South Carolina, post office, and much back-and-forth about whether postmasters were required to deliver this mail.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Postmaster General, they were not.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under the Constitution, the importation of enslaved persons could not be prohibited until 1808 (20 years).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As the end of the 20 years approached, an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves sailed through Congress with little opposition.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] President Jefferson signed it, and it went effect on January 1, 1808.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1820, the Act to Protect the Commerce of the United States and Punish the Crime of Piracy was passed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This law made importing slaves into the United States a death penalty offense.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1830, most Americans were, at least in principle, opposed to slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, opponents of slavery deliberated on how to end the institution, as well as what would become of the slaves once they were free.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1830s there was a progressive shift in thinking in the North.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Mainstream opinion changed from gradual emancipation and resettlement of freed blacks in Africa, sometimes a condition of their manumission, to immediatism: freeing all the slaves immediately and sorting out the problems later.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This change was in many cases sudden, a consequence of the individual's coming in direct contact with the horrors of American slavery, or hearing of them from a credible source.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American beginning of abolitionism as a political movement is usually dated from 1 January 1831, when Wm.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison (as he always signed himself) published the first issue of his new weekly newspaper, *The Liberator* (1831), which appeared without interruption until slavery in the United States was abolished in 1865, when it closed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists included those who joined the American Anti-Slavery Society or its auxiliary groups in the 1830s and 1840s, as the movement fragmented.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The fragmented anti-slavery movement included groups such as the Liberty Party; the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society; the American Missionary Association; and the Church Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Historians traditionally distinguish between moderate anti-slavery reformers or gradualists, who concentrated on stopping the spread of slavery, and radical abolitionists or immediatists, whose demands for unconditional emancipation often merged with a concern for Black civil rights.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nearly all Northern politicians, such as Abraham Lincoln, rejected the "immediate emancipation" called for by the abolitionists, seeing it as "extreme".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, many Northern leaders, including Lincoln, Stephen Douglas (the Democratic nominee in 1860), John C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont (the Republican nominee in 1856), and Ulysses S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Grant married into slave-owning Southern families without any moral qualms.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Anti-slavery as a principle was far more than just the wish to prevent the expansion of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1840, abolitionists rejected this because it let sin continue to exist; they demanded that slavery end everywhere, immediately and completely.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown was the only abolitionist to have actually planned a violent insurrection, though David Walker promoted the idea.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement was strengthened by the activities of free African Americans, especially in the Black church, who argued that the old Biblical justifications for slavery contradicted the New Testament.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] African-American activists and their writings were rarely heard outside the Black community.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, they were tremendously influential on a few sympathetic white people, most prominently the first white activist to reach prominence, Wm.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lloyd Garrison, who was its most effective propagandist.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Garrison's efforts to recruit eloquent spokesmen led to the discovery of ex-slave Frederick Douglass, who eventually became a prominent activist in his own right.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually, Douglass would publish his own widely distributed abolitionist newspaper, *North Star*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1850s, the American abolitionist movement split into two camps over the question of whether the United States Constitution did or did not protect slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This issue arose in the late 1840s after the publication of *The Unconstitutionality of Slavery* by Lysander Spooner.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians, led by Garrison and Wendell Phillips, publicly burned copies of the Constitution, called it a pact with slavery, and demanded its abolition and replacement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another camp, led by Lysander Spooner, Gerrit Smith, and eventually Douglass, considered the Constitution to be an anti-slavery document.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Using an argument based upon Natural Law and a form of social contract theory, they said that slavery fell outside the Constitution's scope of legitimate authority and therefore should be abolished.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another split in the abolitionist movement was along class lines.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The artisan republicanism of Robert Dale Owen and Frances Wright stood in stark contrast to the politics of prominent elite abolitionists such as industrialist Arthur Tappan and his evangelist brother Lewis.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While the former pair opposed slavery on a basis of solidarity of "wage slaves" with "chattel slaves", the Whiggish Tappans strongly rejected this view, opposing the characterization of Northern workers as "slaves" in any sense.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many American abolitionists took an active role in opposing slavery by supporting the Underground Railroad.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was made illegal by the federal Fugitive Slave Law of 1850, arguably the most hated and most openly evaded federal legislation in the nation's history.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Nevertheless, participants like Harriet Tubman, Henry Highland Garnet, Alexander Crummell, Amos Noë Freeman, and others continued with their work.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were particularly active in Ohio, where some worked directly in the Underground Railroad.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Since only the Ohio River separated free Ohio from slave Kentucky, it was a popular destination for fugitive slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Supporters helped them there, in many cases to cross Lake Erie by boat, into Canada.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Western Reserve area of northeast Ohio was "probably the most intensely antislavery section of the country." The Oberlin-Wellington Rescue got national publicity.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionist John Brown grew up in Hudson, Ohio.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the South, members of the abolitionist movement or other people opposing slavery were often targets of lynch mob violence before the American Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His fellow Duffield Street residents Thomas and Harriet Truesdell were leading members of the abolitionist movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Truesdell was a founding member of the Providence Anti-slavery Society before moving to Brooklyn in 1838.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Harriet Truesdell was also very active in the movement, organizing an anti-slavery convention in Pennsylvania Hall (Philadelphia).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Another prominent Brooklyn-based abolitionist was Rev.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Joshua Leavitt, trained as a lawyer at Yale, who stopped practicing law in order to attend Yale Divinity School, and subsequently edited the abolitionist newspaper *The Emancipator* and campaigned against slavery, as well as advocating other social reforms.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1841, Leavitt published *The Financial Power of Slavery*, which argued that the South was draining the national economy due to its reliance on enslaved workers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2007, Duffield Street was given the name Abolitionist Place, and the Truesdells' home at 227 Duffield received landmark status in 2021.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was a direct result of the Union victory in the American Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The central issue of the war was slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the North, most opponents of slavery supported other modernizing reform movements such as the temperance movement, public schooling, and prison- and asylum-building.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They were split on the issue of women's activism and their political role, and this contributed to a major rift in the Society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1839, brothers Arthur Tappan and Lewis Tappan left the Society and formed the American and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society, which did not admit women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Other members of the Society, including Charles Turner Torrey, Amos Phelps, Henry Stanton, and Alanson St.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Clair, in addition to disagreeing with Garrison on the women's issue, urged taking a much more activist approach to abolitionism and consequently challenged Garrison's leadership at the Society's annual meeting in January 1839.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When the challenge was beaten back, they left and founded the New Organization, which adopted a more activist approach to freeing slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Soon after, in 1840, they formed the Liberty Party, which had as its sole platform the abolition of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1840, Garrison himself announced the formation of a third new organization, the Friends of Universal Reform, with sponsors and founding members including prominent reformers Maria Chapman, Abby Kelley Foster, Oliver Johnson, and Bronson Alcott (father of Louisa May Alcott).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists such as William Lloyd Garrison repeatedly condemned slavery for contradicting the principles of freedom and equality on which the country was founded.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most influential abolitionist publication was *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), the best-selling novel by Harriet Beecher Stowe, who had attended the anti-slavery debates at Lane, of which her father, Lyman Beecher, was the president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outraged by the Fugitive Slave Law of 1850 (which made the escape narrative part of everyday news), Stowe emphasized the horrors that abolitionists had long claimed about slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Her depiction of the evil slave owner Simon Legree, a transplanted Yankee who kills the Christ-like Uncle Tom, outraged the North, helped sway British public opinion against the South, and inflamed Southern slave owners who tried to refute it by showing that some slave owners were humanitarian.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It inspired numerous anti-Tom, pro-slavery novels, several written and published by women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to a book reviewer, "Next to *Uncle Tom's Cabin* (1852), Hinton Helper's critique of slavery and the Southern class system, *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857), was arguably the most important antislavery book of the 1850s." According to historian George M.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Two diametrically opposed anti-slavery positions emerged regarding the United States Constitution.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Garrisonians emphasized that the document permitted and protected slavery and was therefore "an agreement with hell" that had to be rejected in favor of immediate emancipation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The mainstream anti-slavery position adopted by the new Republican party argued that the Constitution could and should be used to eventually end slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They assumed that the Constitution gave the government no authority to abolish slavery directly.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, there were multiple tactics available to support the long-term strategy of using the Constitution as a battering ram against the peculiar institution.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] First Congress could block the admission of any new slave states.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] That would steadily move the balance of power in Congress and the Electoral College in favor of freedom.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could abolish slavery in the District of Columbia and the territories.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could use the Commerce Clause to end the interstate slave trade, thereby crippling the steady movement of slavery from the southeast to the southwest.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress could recognize free blacks as full citizens and insist on due process rights to protect fugitive slaves from being captured and returned to bondage.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Finally, the government could use patronage powers to promote the anti-slavery cause across the country, especially in the border states.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Pro-slavery elements considered the Republican strategy to be much more dangerous to their cause than radical abolitionism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln's election was met by secession.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Indeed, the Republican strategy mapped the "crooked path to abolition" that prevailed during the Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1850s, the slave trade remained legal in all 16 states of the American South.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] While slavery was fading away in the cities and border states, it remained strong in plantation areas that grew cash crops such as cotton, sugar, rice, tobacco or hemp.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1860 United States census, the slave population in the United States had grown to four million.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] American abolitionism, after Nat Turner's revolt ended its discussion in the South, was based in the North, and white Southerners alleged it fostered slave rebellion.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The white abolitionist movement in the North was led by social reformers, especially William Lloyd Garrison, founder of the American Anti-Slavery Society, and writers such as John Greenleaf Whittier and Harriet Beecher Stowe.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Black activists included former slaves such as Frederick Douglass, and free blacks such as the brothers Charles Henry Langston and John Mercer Langston, who helped to found the Ohio Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some abolitionists said that slavery was criminal and a sin; they also criticized slave owners for using black women as concubines and taking sexual advantage of them.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 attempted to resolve issues surrounding slavery caused by the War with Mexico and the admission to the Union of the slave Republic of Texas.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Compromise of 1850 was proposed by "The Great Compromiser" Henry Clay; support was coordinated by Senator Stephen A.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Law was a concession to the South.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Abolitionists were outraged, because the new law required Northerners to help in the capture and return of runaway slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1854, Congress passed the Kansas–Nebraska Act, which opened those territories to slavery if the local residents voted that way.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The anti-slavery gains made in previous compromises were reversed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A firestorm of outrage brought together former Whigs, Know-Nothings, and former Free Soil Democrats to form a new party in 1854–56, the Republican Party.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It included a program of rapid modernization involving the government promotion of industry, railroads, banks, free homesteads, and colleges, all to the annoyance of the South.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party denounced the Slave Power – that is the political power of the slave owners who supposedly controlled the national government for their own benefit and to the disadvantage of the ordinary white man.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republicans wanted to achieve the gradual extinction of slavery by market forces, because its members believed that free labor was superior to slave labor.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southern leaders said the Republican policy of blocking the expansion of slavery into the West made them second-class citizens, and challenged their autonomy.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] With the 1860 presidential victory of Abraham Lincoln, seven Deep South states whose economy was based on cotton and slavery decided to secede and form a new nation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War broke out in April 1861 with the firing on Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] When Lincoln called for troops to suppress the rebellion, four more slave states seceded.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The crisis in Kansas Territory and the neighboring slave state of Missouri turned bloody during what was known as the Bleeding Kansas crisis of the 1850s.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Proslavery *border ruffians* and *Bushwhackers* fought antislavery "free-staters" and *Jayhawkers*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Paramilitary guerrilla warfare became widespread in the area, as a prelude to the Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The violence would spread to many other places, including the Senate Chamber of the U.S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Capitol where a Southern Democrat attacked a Northern Republican with a cane as his political allies watched.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Explorer, army veteran, and abolitionist John C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Frémont ran as the first Republican nominee for president in 1856.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The new party crusaded on the slogan: "Free soil, free silver, free men, Frémont and victory!" Although he lost, the party showed a strong base.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It dominated in Yankee areas of New England, New York and the northern Midwest, and had a strong presence in the rest of the North.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] It had almost no support in the South, where it was roundly denounced in 1856–60 as a divisive force that threatened civil war.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The newly-formed Republican Party gained quite a standing in the 1856 to 1857 election cycle in the U.S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] House and Senate, cementing its status as the primary party for abolitionists and northerners for some time.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Without using the term "containment", the new Party in the mid-1850s proposed a system of containing slavery once it gained control of the national government.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Militant abolitionists demanded *immediate* emancipation, not a slow-acting containment.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some rejected the new party, and in turn its leaders reassured voters they were not trying to abolish slavery in the U.S. altogether, which was politically impossible, and were just working against its spread.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] John Brown has been called "the most controversial of all 19th-century Americans".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Whereas Garrison was a pacifist, Brown believed violence was unfortunately necessary to end slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The raid, though unsuccessful in the short term, may have helped Lincoln get elected and moved the Southern states to secede, leading to the Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians regard Brown as a crazed lunatic, while David S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Reynolds hails him as the man who "killed slavery, sparked the civil war, and seeded civil rights".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] His raid in October 1859 involved a band of 22 men who seized the Federal armory at Harper's Ferry, Virginia (since 1863, West Virginia), knowing it contained tens of thousands of weapons.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown believed the South was on the verge of a gigantic slave uprising and that one spark would set it off.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's supporters George Luther Stearns, Franklin B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Sanborn, Thomas Wentworth Higginson, Theodore Parker, Samuel Gridley Howe, and Gerrit Smith were all abolitionists, members of the so-called Secret Six who provided financial backing for Brown's raid.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown's raid, says historian David Potter, "was meant to be of vast magnitude and to produce a revolutionary slave uprising throughout the South".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Brown hoped to have quickly a small army of runaway slaves, but made no provision to inform these potential runaways, although he got a little local support.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Army was dispatched to put down the raid, and Brown was quickly captured.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] He was tried for treason against the Commonwealth of Virginia, murder, and inciting a slave revolt, was found guilty of all charges, and was hanged.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At his trial, Brown exuded a remarkable zeal and single-mindedness that played directly to Southerners' worst fears.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Under Virginia law there was a month between the sentencing and the hanging, and in those weeks Brown spoke gladly with reporters and anyone else who wanted to see him, and wrote many letters.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Few individuals did more to cause secession than John Brown, because Southerners believed he was right about an impending slave revolt.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The day of his execution, Brown prophesied, "the crimes of this guilty land will never be purged away but with blood.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Civil War began with the stated goal of preserving the Union, and Lincoln said repeatedly that on the topic of slavery, he was only opposed to its spread to the Western territories.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This view of the war progressively changed, one step at a time, as public sentiment evolved, until by 1865 the war was seen in the North as primarily concerned with ending slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first federal act taken against slavery during the war occurred on 16 April 1862, when Lincoln signed the District of Columbia Compensated Emancipation Act, which abolished slavery in Washington, D.C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] A few months later, on June 19, Congress banned slavery in all federal territories, fulfilling Lincoln's 1860 campaign promise.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Meanwhile, the Union suddenly found itself dealing with a steady stream of thousands of escaped slaves, achieving freedom, or so they hoped, by crossing Union lines.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In response, Congress passed the Confiscation Acts, which essentially declared escaped slaves from the South to be confiscated war property, and thus did not have to be returned to their Confederate owners.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, effective 1 January 1863, which declared only those slaves in Confederate states to be free.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Colored Troops began operations in 1863.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fugitive Slave Act of 1850 was repealed in June 1864.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Eventually support for abolition was enough to pass the Thirteenth Amendment, ratified in December 1865, which abolished slavery everywhere in the United States, freeing more than 50,000 people still enslaved in Kentucky and Delaware, in 1865 the only states in which slavery still existed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The Thirteenth Amendment also abolished slavery among the Native American tribes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The abolitionist movement began about the time of the United States' independence.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The first abolition organization was the Pennsylvania Abolition Society, which first met in 1775; Benjamin Franklin was its president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The New York Manumission Society was founded in 1785 by powerful politicians: John Jay, Alexander Hamilton, and Aaron Burr.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] There is quite a bit of confusion about when slavery was abolished in the Northern states, because "abolishing slavery" meant different things in different states.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] These included the first abolition laws in the entire New World: the Massachusetts Constitution, adopted in 1780, declared all men to have rights, making slavery unenforceable, and it disappeared through the individual actions of both masters and slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, what the abolition forces passed in 1799 in New York State was an Act for the *gradual* abolition of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slavery in New York did not officially end until 1827, and more than 70 enslaved people in New York appeared on the 1830 decennial census.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] No slaves appeared in the state's 1840 census.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] New Jersey abolished slavery in 1804, but in 1860 a dozen black people were still held as "perpetual apprentices".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Northwest Ordinance of 1787, the Congress of the Confederation prohibited slavery in the territories northwest of the Ohio River.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] At the Constitutional Convention of 1787, slavery was the most contentious topic.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Outright prohibition of slavery was impossible, because the Southern states (Georgia, South Carolina, North Carolina, Virginia, Maryland, and Delaware) would never have agreed to it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The only restriction on slavery that was agreed to was to allow Congress to prohibit the importation of slaves, and even that was postponed for 20 years.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By that time, all the states except South Carolina had laws abolishing or severely limiting the importation of slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] As he put it, this would "withdraw the citizens of the United States from all further participation in those violations of human rights...which the morality, the reputation, and the best of our country have long been eager to proscribe".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, about 1,000 slaves per year continued to be illegally brought (smuggled) into the United States; see Wanderer and Clotilda.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This was primarily via Spanish Florida and the Gulf Coast; the United States acquired Florida from Spain in 1819, effective 1821, in part as a slave-control measure: no imports coming in, and certainly no fugitives escaping into a refuge.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Congress declined to pass any restriction on the lucrative interstate slave trade, which expanded to replace the supply of African slaves (see Slavery in the United States#Slave trade).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] After 1776, Quaker and Moravian advocates helped persuade numerous slaveholders in the Upper South to free their slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Manumissions increased for nearly two decades.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Many individual acts by slaveholders freed thousands of slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Slaveholders freed slaves in such numbers that the percentage of free black people in the Upper South increased from 1 to 10 percent, with most of that increase in Virginia, Maryland and Delaware.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1810 three-quarters of blacks in Delaware were free.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The most notable of men offering freedom was Robert Carter III of Virginia, who freed more than 450 people by "Deed of Gift", filed in 1791.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] This number was more slaves than any single American had freed before or after.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Often slaveholders came to their decisions by their own struggles in the Revolution; their wills and deeds frequently cited language about the equality of men supporting the decision to set slaves free.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The era's changing economy also encouraged slaveholders to release slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Planters were shifting from labor-intensive tobacco to mixed-crop cultivation and needed fewer slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1860, 91.7% of the blacks in Delaware and 49.7% of those in Maryland were free.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Such early free families often formed the core of artisans, professionals, preachers, and teachers in future generations.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] However, this did not signal racial equality.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Though free from slavery, blacks still faced immense discrimination.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] For example, Delaware affirmed and reaffirmed black disenfranchisement several times throughout the late 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Delaware's General Assembly enacted harsh black codes throughout the 19th century that restricted travel, property ownership, expression, and socialization for African Americans.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The amendment failed and Missouri became a slave state.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] According to historian David Brion Davis, this may have been the first time in the world that a political leader openly attacked slavery's perceived legality in such a radical manner.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Postmaster General refused to allow the mails to carry abolition pamphlets to the South.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Northern teachers suspected of abolitionism were expelled from the South, and abolitionist literature was banned.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] One Northerner, Amos Dresser (1812–1904), in 1835 was tried in Nashville, Tennessee, for possessing anti-slavery publications, convicted, and as punishment was whipped publicly.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Southerners rejected the denials of Republicans that they were abolitionists.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] They pointed to John Brown's attempt in 1859 to start a slave uprising as proof that multiple Northern conspiracies were afoot to ignite slave rebellions.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Although some abolitionists did call for slave revolts, no evidence of any other Brown-like conspiracy has been discovered.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The North felt threatened as well, for as Eric Foner concludes, "northerners came to view slavery as the very antithesis of the good society, as well as a threat to their own fundamental values and interests".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The famous, "fiery" abolitionist Abby Kelley Foster, from Massachusetts, was considered an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in full civil rights for all black people.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She held to the view that the freed slaves would colonize Liberia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Parts of the anti-slavery movement became known as "Abby Kellyism".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] She recruited Susan B Anthony and Lucy Stone to the movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] Effingham Capron, a cotton and textile scion, who attended the Quaker meeting where Abby Kelley Foster and her family were members, became a prominent abolitionist at the local, state, and national levels.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p01] The local anti-slavery society at Uxbridge, Massachusetts, had more than 25% of the town's population as members.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] McPherson in 1964 defined an abolitionist "as one who before the Civil War had agitated for the immediate, unconditional and total abolition of slavery in the United States".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He notes that many historians have used a broader definition without his emphasis on immediacy.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Thus he does not include opponents of slavery such as Abraham Lincoln or the Republican Party; they called for the immediate end to expansion of slavery before 1861.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As such, abolitionism in the United States was identified by historians as an expression of moralism, it often operated in tandem with another social reform effort, the temperance movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was also attacked, to a lesser degree, as harmful on economic grounds.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evidence was that the South, with many enslaved African Americans on plantations, was definitely poorer than the North, which had few.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Historians and scholars have largely overlooked the work of black abolitionists; instead, they have focused on only a few black abolitionists, such as Frederick Douglass.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Yet lesser-known black abolitionists, such as Martin Delany and James Monroe Whitfield, also played an undeniably large role in shaping the movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionists had the distinct problem of having to confront an often-hostile American public, while still acknowledging their nationality and struggle.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As a result, many black abolitionists "intentionally adopted aspects of British, New England, and Midwestern cultures".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Furthermore, much of abolitionist rhetoric, and black abolitionist rhetoric in particular, were influenced by the Puritan preaching heritage.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Frederick Douglass was a notable black abolitionist, who significantly contributed to the transnational abolitionist movement through his lecture tours of the United Kingdom from 1845 to 1847.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In particular, he had a connection with Daniel O'Connell: Both O'Connell and Douglass strongly opposed slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] On 4 October 1845, the British and Foreign Anti-Slavery Society gave Douglass a Bible bound in gold.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] African Americans, with Douglass being a key example, were involving themselves in US foreign relations and influencing British anti-slavery rhetoric.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass was best known for his speeches, and he completed 280 lectures across the UK and Ireland in the 19 months that he was there.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric discussed relationships between power, race, and the popular imagination, showing the complexities of the morality and representation of the abolitionist debate.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass and other black nationalists capitalised on pre-existing political and ideological debates among the UK to reassert the need for abolitionism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In general, Black female abolitionists had separate motives and rhetorical strategies than White female abolitionists.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were often middle class and members of literary societies; the ones to which they belonged were often made up of solely Black women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their activist efforts, they held themselves to high moral standards to be viewed as legitimate by others.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sarah Mapps Douglass, a free-born Quaker who wrote articles for *The Liberator* on abolition also served as the secretary for a literary society for women in Philadelphia, where she emphasized the importance of education and morality for Black women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women that escaped slavery would sometimes write and publish their slave narratives as a way to argue for abolition.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In opposition to male slave narratives, like Frederick Douglass's, which highlighted literacy, Black women emphasized the communities and relationships they formed as keys to their humanity and right to freedom.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were also keen to highlight their relationship to motherhood, so as to emphasize their shared traits with white women and the ways in which they too could meet traditional expectations of white women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Jacobs's *Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl* showcases her grandmother as the matriarch of her family, which shows how enslaved mothers are capable of nurturing like valued white women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women also played their role in the abolitionist movement, both domestically and internationally, showing involvement in US Foreign Relations.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable example was Harriet Jacobs, who produced letters in England reflecting on her experiences as a slave in the US to challenge the pro-slavery movement in the USA.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The London Emancipation Committee published her letters into a book, titled: The Deeper Wrong: Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl, Written by Herself.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The book was not just noticed in reform journals, but in the mainstream press.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lengthy British reviews show how the book helped abolitionists win public support in Britain.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric could be done in literary form, a way for black women to have influence in an international abolitionist movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not only a transatlantic movement between Britain and the US, it also had influence in the Caribbean and South America.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1833 legal case Mundrucu v Barker also carried international importance in the abolitionist campaign.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In taking a stand against segregation, a black Brazilian immigrant had focused worldwide attention on racism in slaveholding US society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Here there was division between white Philadelphians who saw black Saint Dominguan refugees as a threat to the city and country's racial order, their way of trying to justify slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This shows the connection between attitudes towards segregation and slavery helped shape black abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This led to domestic organisations being established by interracial communities, such as the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Working as Jamaican-based writers for New York newspapers between 1840 and 1851, the two black US-Jamaican brothers, Henry and George Davison provided inter-American perspectives on abolitionism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Henry wrote letters to the National Anti-Slavery Standard.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black Americans had opportunities to write for newspapers, providing publicity and discussion of abolitionist rhetoric.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slavery was moving beyond internal US divisions, but reaching influence outside of the USA.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black abolitionist rhetoric was not simply an African-American activity, but involved South American and Caribbean individuals too, showing an international movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina and Sarah Grimké were the first female anti-slavery agents, and played a variety of roles in the abolitionist movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though born in the South, the Grimké sisters became disillusioned with slavery and moved North to get away from it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Perhaps because of their birthplace, the Grimké sisters' critiques carried particular weight and specificity.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Angelina Grimké spoke of her thrill at seeing white men do manual labor of any kind.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their perspectives as native Southerners as well as women, brought a new important point of view to the abolitionist movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1836, they moved to New York and began work for the Anti-Slavery Society, where they met and were impressed by William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The sisters wrote many pamphlets (Angelina's "Appeal to the Christian Women of the South" was the only appeal directly to Southern women to defy slavery laws) and played leadership roles at the first Anti-Slavery Convention of American Women in 1837.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimkés later made a notable speaking tour around the north, which culminated in Angelina's February 1838 address to a Committee of the Legislature of Massachusetts.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lucretia Mott was also active in the abolitionist movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though well known for her women's suffrage advocacy, Mott also played an important role in the abolitionist movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] During four decades, she delivered sermons about abolitionism, women's rights, and a host of other issues.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott acknowledged her Quaker beliefs' determinative role in affecting her abolitionist sentiment.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster, with a strong Quaker heritage, helped lead Susan B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony and Lucy Stone into the abolition movement, and encouraged them to take on a role in political activism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] the first National Women's Rights Convention, held in Worcester, Massachusetts, in 1850.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The better-known Seneca Falls Convention, held in 1848, was not national).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She was an "ultra" abolitionist who believed in immediate and complete civil rights for all slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 1841, however, she had resigned from the Quakers over disputes about not allowing anti-slavery speakers in meeting houses (including the Uxbridge monthly meeting where she had attended with her family), and the group disowned her.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley became a leading speaker and the leading fundraiser for the American Anti-slavery Society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Radical abolitionism became known as "Abby Kelleyism".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Other leaders in the abolitionist movement were Lydia Maria Child, Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Susan B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony, Harriet Tubman, and Sojourner Truth.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But even beyond these well-known women, abolitionism maintained impressive support from white middle-class and some black women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was these women who performed many of the logistical, day-to-day tasks that made the movement successful.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They raised money, wrote and distributed propaganda pieces, drafted and signed petitions, and lobbied the legislatures.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Though abolitionism sowed the seeds of the women's rights movement, most women became involved in abolitionism because of a gendered religious worldview, and the idea that they had feminine, moral responsibilities.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in the winter of 1831–1832, women sent three petitions to the Virginia legislature, advocating emancipation of the state's slave population.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The only precedent for such action was Catharine Beecher's organization of a petition protesting the Cherokee removal.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Virginia petitions, while the first of their kind, were by no means the last.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Similar backing increased leading up to the Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even as women played crucial roles in abolitionism, the movement simultaneously helped stimulate women's-rights efforts.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A full 10 years before the Seneca Falls Convention, the Grimké sisters were travelling and lecturing about their experiences with slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As Gerda Lerner says, the Grimkés understood their actions' great impact.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "In working for the liberation of the slave," Lerner writes, "Sarah and Angelina Grimké found the key to their own liberation.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And the consciousness of the significance of their actions was clearly before them.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women gained important experiences in public speaking and organizing that stood them in good stead going forward.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Grimké sisters' public speaking played a critical part in legitimizing women's place in the public sphere.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Some Christian women created cent societies to benefit abolition movements, where many women in a church would each pledge to donate one cent a week to help abolitionist causes.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even though women were not allowed full access to political and religious spaces, they still played a big role in the abolitionist movement through both public activism and behind-the-scenes activism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] As historian Julie Roy Jeffrey explains, a lot of women relied on their religious faith and authority to speak out against slavery and challenge male-led church systems that tried to keep them quiet.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They believed slavery went against Christian values and saw it as a deep moral wrong.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In their speeches and writing, they made it clear that true faith could not exist alongside a system that discriminated against people.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Women like Sarah Otis Ernst and Maria Child used persuasive writing, public speeches, and organizing work to fight not just slavery, but also the powerful systems that kept it going.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ernst was a strong Garrisonian who got frustrated when mainstream abolitionists started watering down their message.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She did not like that people in the movement were trying to be more politically strategic instead of sticking to the original beliefs, like full racial equality, immediate emancipation, and refusing to work with pro-slavery systems.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the 1852 American and Foreign Antislavery Society convention, around two-thirds of the 2,000 people there were women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] That says a lot about how involved women were, even though they often got written out of the story.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not vote, but they used writing, speeches, and journalism to influence politics and public opinion.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Their activism was real, public, and tied directly into national conversations.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But not all women approached the movement the same way.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were clear differences between how white and Black women operated, and sometimes those differences caused conflict.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women, especially ones who were more religious, focused a lot on the moral and spiritual arguments.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They used Christian values to call out slavery as a sin and tried to appeal to other white Americans by framing it as a moral crisis.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Lydia Maria Child wrote about Christian duty and compassion to get people on board.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But that type of activism did not always connect with what Black women were facing every day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] And even inside the abolitionist circles, Black women were still often pushed to the side.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not always given speaking time, leadership roles, or space in published work.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sojourner Truth had to fight just to speak at some events, and even then, people questioned her.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] White women could usually speak and be heard if they used moral language.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women had to work twice as hard just to get into the room.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They faced racism from inside the movement and also from the outside world, which made it even harder for their voices to be heard.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Richmond talks about how central Black women were to abolition, even though they have been left out of most of the history.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Women like Sojourner Truth, Maria Stewart, and Harriet Tubman struggled not only for the abolition of slavery but for gender and racial equality as well".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were not just giving speeches, they were founding antislavery groups, organizing communities, and building transatlantic networks.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They were working through both racism and sexism and still finding ways to be powerful voices.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Truth's line "Ain’t I a Woman?" and Stewart saying she had to "stand for justice wherever I find it" show how they were calling out not just slavery, but the whole system that tried to silence them.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Harriet Tubman took a different route; she led people to freedom through the Underground Railroad and even worked for the Union Army.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black women's abolitionism looked different from that of white women.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was rooted in their personal experience and often more direct and action-focused.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They made sure the fight for abolition was not just about ending slavery, but also about achieving full equality and justice.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The July 1848 Seneca Falls Convention grew out of a partnership between Lucretia Mott and Elizabeth Cady Stanton that blossomed while the two worked, at first, on abolitionist issues.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Indeed, the two met at the World's Anti-Slavery Convention in the summer of 1840.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Mott brought oratorical skills and an impressive reputation as an abolitionist to the nascent women's rights movement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism brought together active women and enabled them to make political and personal connections while honing communication and organizational skills.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Even Sojourner Truth, commonly associated with abolitionism, delivered her first documented public speech at the 1850 National Women's Rights Convention in Worcester.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There, she argued for women's reform activism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The religious component of American abolitionism was great.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It began with the Quakers, then moved to the other Protestants with the Second Great Awakening of the early 19th century.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Saying slavery was sinful made its evil easy to understand, and tended to arouse fervor for the cause.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The debate about slavery was often based on what the Bible said or did not say about it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John Brown, who had studied the Bible for the ministry, proclaimed that he was "an instrument of God".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Second Great Awakening of the 1820s and 1830s in religion inspired groups that undertook many types of social reform.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For some that included the immediate abolition of slavery as they considered it sinful to hold slaves as well as to tolerate slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Opposition to slavery, for example, was one of the works of piety of the Methodist Churches, which were established by John Wesley.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Abolitionist" had several meanings at the time.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The followers of William Lloyd Garrison, including Wendell Phillips and Frederick Douglass, demanded the "immediate abolition of slavery", hence the name, also called "immediatism".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A more pragmatic group of abolitionists, such as Theodore Weld and Arthur Tappan, wanted immediate action, but were willing to support a program of gradual emancipation, with a long intermediate stage.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The *True Wesleyan* a periodical founded by Orange Scott and Jotham Horton was used to disseminate abolitionist views.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Methodist and Quaker branches of Christianity played an integral part in the formulation of abolitionist ideology in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Anti-slavery men", such as John Quincy Adams, did not call slavery a sin.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They called it an evil feature of society as a whole.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They did what they could to limit slavery and end it where possible, but were not part of any abolitionist group.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, in 1841, John Quincy Adams represented the *Amistad* African slaves in the Supreme Court of the United States and argued that they should be set free.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the last years before the war, "anti-slavery" could refer to the Northern majority, such as Abraham Lincoln, who opposed expansion of slavery or its influence, as by the Kansas–Nebraska Act or the Fugitive Slave Act.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many Southerners called all these abolitionists, without distinguishing them from the Garrisonians.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics in the United States seldom challenged the role of slavery in society as it was protected at that time by the U.S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They viewed the abolitionists as anti-Catholic and anti-Irish.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish Catholics were generally well received by Democrats in the South.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, most Irish Nationalists and Fenians supported the abolition of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Daniel O'Connell, the Catholic leader of the Irish in Ireland, supported abolition in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He organized a petition in Ireland with 60,000 signatures urging the Irish of the United States to support abolition.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] John O'Mahony, a founder of the Irish Republican Brotherhood was an abolitionist and served as colonel in the 69th Infantry Regiment during the Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Irish Catholics in the United States were recent immigrants; most were poor and very few owned slaves.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They had to compete with free blacks for unskilled labor jobs.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They saw abolitionism as the militant wing of evangelical anti-Catholic Protestantism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Catholic Church in the United States had long ties in slaveholding Maryland and Louisiana.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1861, the Archbishop of New York wrote to Secretary of War Cameron: "That the Church is opposed to slavery ...
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Her doctrine on that subject is, that it is a crime to reduce men naturally free to a condition of servitude and bondage, as slaves." No American bishop supported extra-political abolition or interference with states' rights before the Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The secular Germans of the Forty-Eighter immigration were largely anti-slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Prominent Forty-Eighters included Carl Schurz and Friedrich Hecker.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] German Lutherans seldom took a position on slavery, but German Methodists were anti-slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both Garrison's newspaper *The Liberator* and his book *Thoughts on African Colonization* (1832) arrived shortly after publication at Western Reserve College, in Hudson, Ohio, which was briefly the center of abolitionist discourse in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (John Brown grew up in Hudson.) The readers, including college president Charles Backus Storrs, found Garrison's arguments and evidence convincing.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolition versus colonization rapidly became the primary issue on the campus, to the point that Storrs complained in writing that nothing else was being discussed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The college's chaplain and theology professor Beriah Green said that "his *Thoughts* and his paper (*The Liberator*) are worthy of the eye and the heart of every American." Green delivered in the college chapel in November and December 1832 four sermons supporting immediate abolition of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These so offended the college's trustees, more conservative than either the students or the faculty, that Green resigned, expecting that he would be fired.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Elizur Wright, another professor, resigned soon afterwards and became the first secretary of the American Anti-Slavery Society, of which Green was the first president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Storrs contracted tuberculosis, took a leave of absence, and died within six months.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This left the school with only one of its four professors.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Green was soon hired as the new president of the Oneida Institute.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under the previous president, George Washington Gale, there had been a mass walkout of students; among the issues was Gale's lack of support for abolition.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He accepted the position on conditions that 1) he be allowed to preach "immediatism", immediate emancipation, and 2) that African-American students be admitted on the same terms as white students.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These were accepted, and we know the names of 16 Blacks who studied there.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Native American students, of whom we know the names of two, were openly accepted as well.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under Green, Oneida became "a hotbed of anti-slavery activity." It was "abolitionist to the core, more so than any other American college." For Presbyterian minister and Bible professor Green, slavery was not just an evil but a sin, and abolitionism was what Christ's principles mandated.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Under him a cadre of abolitionists was trained, who then carried the abolitionist message, via lectures and sermons, throughout the North.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many future well-known black leaders and abolitionists were students at Oneida while Green was president.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These include William Forten (son of James Forten), Alexander Crummell, Rev.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Oneida Institute did not have an incident, like that of Western Reserve, which brought national attention to it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Its successor, Lane Seminary, in Cincinnati, did.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] "Lane was Oneida moved west." Leading the exodus from Oneida was a former Oneida student, and private student of Gale before that, Theodore Dwight Weld.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He greatly impressed the philanthropist brothers and abolitionists Arthur and Lewis Tappan.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They hired him to report on the movement nationally, and specifically to find a new location for their funding, since Oneida, a manual labor school, was a disappointment, according to Weld and his student followers.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] At the same time that Weld was scouting a location for a new school, the barely-functioning Lane Seminary was looking for students.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Based on Weld's recommendation, the Tappans started giving Lane the financial support they had previously given Oneida.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld, though on paper enrolled as a student at Lane, was de facto its head, choosing, through his recommendations to the Tappans, the president (Lyman Beecher, after Charles Grandison Finney, who became later the second president of Oberlin, turned it down), and telling the trustees whom to hire.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The group of students led by Weld constituted the first student movement in the history of the country.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He chose Lane, and they followed him there.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When he soon left Lane for another new, struggling institution, Oberlin, they did so too, as a group.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Students, many of whom considered him the real leader of Lane, responded to Weld's announcement of the new school in Cincinnati.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lane ended up with about 100 students, the most of any seminary in America.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One of Weld's key contentions (and of Puritan abolition sentiment in general) was that slavery was inherently anti-family.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] While slave marriage was illegal, it happened frequently.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners expected their slaves to have many children to replace their numbers; Virginia and Maryland "exported" slaves to the Deep South—they were an asset like cattle—after Congress had banned the importation of slaves in 1808.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Since slaves were property they were frequently bought and sold, ripping apart families.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In his 1839 book *American Slavery as It Is*, Weld showed just how brutal the slave trade was towards families.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] To the very family-focused Puritans, this was one of the greatest crimes of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Weld's descriptions of families destroyed would later serve as the basis for scenes in *Uncle Tom's Cabin*, including Uncle Tom's being sold and separated from the children.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] No sooner had this disparate group of former Oneida students and others arrived at Lane, under the leadership of Weld, than they formed an anti-slavery society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They then proceeded to hold a well-publicized series of debates on abolition versus African colonization, lasting 18 evenings, and decided that abolition was a much better solution to slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In fact no real debate took place, since no one appeared to defend colonization.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] These "debates", which were well publicized, alarmed Lane's president Lyman Beecher and the school's trustees.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Adding to their alarm were the classes the students were holding in the Black community, teaching Blacks to read.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Fearing violence, since Cincinnati was strongly anti-abolitionist (see Cincinnati riots of 1829), they immediately prohibited any future such "off-the-topic" discussions and activities.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The students, again led by Weld, felt that abolitionism was so important – it was their responsibility as Christians to promote it – and they resigned *en masse*, joined by Asa Mahan, a trustee who supported the students.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] With support from the Tappans, they briefly tried to establish a new seminary, but as this did not prove a practical solution they accepted a proposal that they move as a group to the new Oberlin Collegiate Institute.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to its students' anti-slavery position, Oberlin soon became one of the most liberal colleges and accepted African-American students.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Along with Garrison, Northcutt and Collins were proponents of immediate abolition.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abby Kelley Foster became an "ultra abolitionist" and a follower of William Lloyd Garrison.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Anthony as well as Elizabeth Cady Stanton into the anti-slavery cause.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] After 1840, "abolition" usually referred to positions similar to Garrison's.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It was largely an ideological movement led by about 3,000 people, including free blacks and free people of color, many of whom, such as Frederick Douglass in Rochester, New York, and Robert Purvis and James Forten in Philadelphia, played prominent leadership roles.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Douglass became legally free during a two-year stay in England, as British supporters raised funds to purchase his freedom from his American owner Thomas Auld, and also helped fund his abolitionist newspapers in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionism had a strong religious base including Quakers, and people converted by the revivalist fervor of the Second Great Awakening, led by Charles Finney in the North, in the 1830s.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Belief in abolition contributed to the formation of Christian denominations, such as the Free Methodist Church.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Evangelical abolitionists founded some colleges, most notably Bates College in Maine and Oberlin College in Ohio.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement attracted such figures as Yale president Noah Porter and Harvard president Thomas Hill.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the mid nineteenth century, American abolitionism was shaped by British ideological and organisational influences.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A key part of this exchange was the intersection of abolitionism and free trade ideology.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] British reformers such as Richard Cobden and the Anti Corn Law League inspired American abolitionists to promote free trade arguing that it was morally and economically aligned to abolition in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Leaders like Joshua Leavitt, campaigner for the Liberty Party, argued that repealing British tariffs would reduce US reliance on Southern slave grown cotton and open markets to free labour goods from the North.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another prominent British activist was George Thompson, who toured the US several times where he delivered speeches connecting Free Trade to the American abolition cause.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Figures like Cobden and Thompson were a direct influence on the ideology of Lloyd Garrison.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Another movement called the Free-produce movement extended across the Atlantic.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] This movement aimed to boycott goods produced by enslaved Africans.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The movement was connected to British activist Joseph Sturge and the idea that a free market allowed for consumer morality.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Sociologist Cecilia Walsh-Russo developed the term 'mutual brokerage' to refer to the interchange of ideas within UK-US abolitionist movements.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She refers to the interactions which allowed ideas and political strategy to co-develop, rather than suggesting one learned from the other.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Walsh-Russo cites the 1840 World Anti-Slavery Convention in London as an example of mutual brokerage.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] She claims the exclusion of women as delegates, despite their presence at the events forced transatlantic abolitionist to re-assess their understanding of political participation and democracy, often leading to more progressive views in UK and US activism.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Despite exclusion from the conference women asserted their right to participate in the abolitionist cause by using informal setting such as salons to promote abolition.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] William Lloyd Garrison also engaged in Irish politics.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He communicated with key figures like Daniel O'Connell, which shaped his understanding of abolition as 'universal emancipation'.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonian abolitionists also used Ireland and the Irish as tools of comparison especially in combatting the American Colonization Society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] However, efforts to forge direct relations between Irish Americans and African Americans largely failed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The 1842 Address from the People of Ireland to Their Countrymen and Countrywomen in America, written by Irish abolitionists and signed by O'Connell, urged Irish Americans to support abolition and racial equality.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrisonians hoped this would foster diasporic responsibility among the Irish but it was rejected by most.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Irish immigrants, perhaps due to a desire to assimilate in the US, were overall not supportive of the abolitionist cause.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] It is easy to overstate the support for abolitionism in the North.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of white Southerners, though by no means all, supported slavery; there was a growing feeling in favor of emancipation in North Carolina, Maryland, Virginia, and Kentucky, until the panic resulting from Nat Turner's 1831 revolt put an end to it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] But only a minority in the North supported abolition, seen as an extreme, "radical" measure.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (See Radical Republicans.) Horace Greeley remarked in 1854 that he had "never been able to discover any strong, pervading, over-ruling Anti Slavery sentiment in the Free States." Free blacks were subject in the North as well as in the South to conditions almost inconceivable today (2019).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Although the picture is neither uniform nor static, in general free blacks in the North were not citizens and could neither vote nor hold public office.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] They could not give testimony in court and their word was never taken against a white man's word, as a result of which white crimes against blacks were rarely punished.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Black children could not study in the public schools, even though Black taxpayers helped support them, and there were only a handful of schools for Black students, like the African Free School in New York, the Abiel Smith School in Boston, and the Watkins Academy for Negro Youth in Baltimore.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] When schools for negroes were set up in Ohio in the 1830s, the teacher of one slept in it every night "for fear whites would burn it", and at another, "a vigilance committee threatened to tar and feather [the teacher] and ride her on a rail if she did not leave".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (Oberlin Collegiate Institute was the first college that survived to admit them by policy; the Oneida Institute was a short-lived predecessor.) In wages, housing, access to services, and transportation, separate but equal or Jim Crow treatment would have been a great improvement.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The proposal to create the country's first college for negros, in New Haven, Connecticut, got such strong local opposition (New Haven Excitement) that it was quickly abandoned.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Schools in which blacks and whites studied together in Canaan, New Hampshire, and Canterbury, Connecticut, were physically destroyed by mobs.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (The prosecutor was Francis Scott Key.) In Savannah, Georgia, the mayor and alderman protected an abolitionist visitor from a mob.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the North there was far more serious violence by mobs, what the press sometimes called "mobocracy".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Lovejoy, who published an abolitionist newspaper, was killed by a mob in Illinois.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Only six months later, the large, modern, and expensive new hall which the Pennsylvania Anti-Slavery Society built in Philadelphia in 1838, was burned by a mob three days after it opened.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] There were other anti-abolitionist riots in New York (1834), Cincinnati (1829, 1836, and 1841), Norwich, Connecticut (1834), Washington, D.C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] (1835), Philadelphia (1842), and Granville, Ohio (following the Ohio State Anti-Slavery Convention, 1836), although there was also a pro-abolition riot (more precisely a pro-fugitive slave riot) in Boston in 1836 (and see Jerry Rescue).
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Between 1835 and 1838, anti-abolitionist violence "settled into a routine feature of public life in virtually all the major northern cities".
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Giving to blacks the same rights that whites had, as Garrison called for, was "far outside the mainstream of opinion in the 1830s." Some opposed even allowing blacks to join abolitionist organizations.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists nationwide were outraged by the murder of white abolitionist and journalist Elijah Parish Lovejoy by a proslavery mob in Alton, Illinois on 7 November 1837.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Six months later, Pennsylvania Hall, an abolitionist venue in Philadelphia, was burnt to the ground by another proslavery mob on May 17, 1838.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Both events contributed to the growing American debate over slavery and marked an increase in violence against abolitionists in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Amos Dresser, a participant in the Lane Debates, was publicly whipped in Nashville.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] A gallows with a note from "Judge Lynch" was erected in front of Garrison's office.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] He, along with the Tappans, was hung in effigy in Charleston, S.C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern post offices burned rather than delivered abolitionist publications, in which they were supported by the national Post Office.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners were angry over the attacks on what some Southerners (including the politician John C.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Calhoun) referred to as their "peculiar institution" of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1830s, Southerners developed a vehement and growing ideological defense of slavery.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Slave owners claimed that slavery was not a necessary evil, or an evil of any sort; slavery was a positive good for masters and slaves alike, and it was explicitly sanctioned by God.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Biblical arguments were made in defense of slavery by religious leaders such as the Rev.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Ross and political leaders such as Jefferson Davis.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Southern Biblical interpretations contradicted those of the abolitionists; a popular one was that the curse on Noah's son Ham and his descendants in Africa justified enslaving blacks.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Abolitionists responded, denying that either God or the Bible endorses slavery, at least as practiced in the Antebellum South.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In the early 19th century, a variety of organizations were established that advocated relocation of black people from the United States, most prominently the American Colonization Society (ACS), founded in 1816.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The ACS enjoyed the support of prominent Southern leaders such as Henry Clay and James Monroe, who saw it as a convenient means of relocating free blacks, whom they perceived as a threat to their control over enslaved blacks.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Starting in the 1820s, the ACS and affiliated state societies assisted a few thousand free blacks to move to the newly established colonies in West Africa that were to form the Republic of Liberia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] From 1832 onward most of the migrants were enslaved people who had been freed on the condition that they go to Liberia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Many migrants died of local diseases, but enough survived for Liberia to declare independence in 1847.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Americo-Liberians formed a ruling elite whose treatment of the native population followed the lines of disdain for African culture they had acquired in America.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Most African Americans opposed colonization, and simply wanted to be given the rights of free citizens in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] One notable opponent of such plans was the wealthy free black abolitionist James Forten of Philadelphia.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1832, prominent white abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison published his book *Thoughts on African Colonization*, in which he attacked severely the policy of sending blacks to (not "back to") Africa, and specifically the American Colonization Society.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] The Colonization Society, which he had previously supported, is "a creature without heart, without brains, eyeless, unnatural, hypocritical, relentless and unjust." "Colonization", according to Garrison, was not a plan to eliminate slavery, but to protect it.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/abolitionism-in-the-united-states-p02] Garrison also pointed out that a majority of the colonists died of disease, and the number of free blacks actually resettled in the future Liberia was minute in comparison to the number of slaves in the United States.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The **Battle of Hampton Roads**, also referred to as the **Battle of the *Monitor* and *Merrimack*** or the **Battle of Ironclads**, was a naval battle during the American Civil War.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was fought over two days, March 8 and 9, 1862, in Hampton Roads, a roadstead in Virginia where the Elizabeth and Nansemond rivers meet the James River just before it flows into Chesapeake Bay by the city of Norfolk.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was a part of the effort of the Confederacy to break the Union blockade, which had cut off Virginia's largest cities and major industrial centers, Norfolk and Richmond, from international trade.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] This battle was significant in that it was the first combat between ironclad warships, the USS *Monitor* and CSS *Virginia*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate fleet consisted of the ironclad ram *Virginia* (built from remnants of the burned steam frigate USS *Merrimack*) and several supporting vessels.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the first day of battle, they were opposed by several conventional, wooden-hulled ships of the Union Navy.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] On that day, the *Virginia* was able to destroy two ships of the Union flotilla, USS *Congress* and USS *Cumberland*, and was about to attack a third, USS *Minnesota*, which had run aground.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, the action was halted by darkness and falling tide, so *Virginia* retired to take care of her few wounded—which included her captain, Flag Officer Franklin Buchanan—and repair her minimal battle damage.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Determined to complete the destruction of *Minnesota*, Catesby ap Roger Jones, acting as captain in Buchanan's absence, returned the ship to the fray the next morning, March 9.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the night, however, the ironclad *Monitor* had arrived and had taken a position to defend *Minnesota*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] When *Virginia* approached, *Monitor* intercepted her.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The two ironclads fought for about three hours, with neither able to inflict significant damage on the other.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The duel ended indecisively, *Virginia* returning to her home at the Gosport Navy Yard for repairs and strengthening, and *Monitor* to her station defending *Minnesota*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The ships did not fight again, and the blockade remained in place.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle received worldwide attention, having immediate effects on navies around the world.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The preeminent naval powers, Great Britain and France, halted further construction of wooden-hulled ships, and others followed suit.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although Britain and France had been engaged in an iron-clad arms race since the 1830s, the Battle of Hampton Roads signaled a new age of naval warfare had arrived for the whole world.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] A new type of warship, monitor, was produced on the principle of the original.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of a small number of very heavy guns, mounted so that they could fire in all directions, was first demonstrated by *Monitor* but soon became standard in warships of all types.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shipbuilders also incorporated rams into the designs of warship hulls for the rest of the century.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 19, 1861, shortly after the outbreak of hostilities at Charleston Harbor, US President Abraham Lincoln proclaimed a blockade of ports in the seceded states.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 27, after Virginia and North Carolina had also passed ordinances of secession, the blockade was extended to include their ports also.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Even before the extension, local troops had seized the Norfolk area and threatened the Gosport Navy Yard in Portsmouth.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The commandant there, Captain Charles S.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] McCauley, though loyal to the Union, was immobilized by advice he received from his subordinate officers, most of whom were in favor of secession.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although he had orders from (Union) Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles to move his ships to Northern ports, he refused to act until April 20, when he gave orders to scuttle the ships in the yard and destroy its facilities.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] At least nine ships were burned, among them the screw frigate USS *Merrimack*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Merrimack* burned only to the waterline, however, and her engines were more or less intact.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The destruction of the navy yard was mostly ineffective; in particular, the large drydock there was relatively undamaged and soon could be restored.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Without firing a shot, the advocates of secession had gained for the South its largest navy yard, as well as the hull and engines of what would be in time its most famous warship.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] They had also seized more than a thousand heavy guns, plus gun carriages and large quantities of gunpowder.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Norfolk and its navy yard in Portsmouth, the Confederacy controlled the southern side of Hampton Roads.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] To prevent Union warships from attacking the yard, the Confederates set up batteries at Sewell's Point and Craney Island, at the juncture of the Elizabeth River with the James.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] (See map.) The Union retained possession of Fort Monroe, at Old Point Comfort on the Virginia Peninsula.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] They also held a small man-made island known as the Rip Raps, on the far side of the channel opposite Fort Monroe, and on this island they completed another fort, named Fort Wool.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Fort Monroe went control of the lower Peninsula as far as Newport News.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Forts Monroe and Wool gave the Union forces control of the entrance to Hampton Roads.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade, initiated on April 30, 1861, cut off Norfolk and Richmond from the sea almost completely.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] To further the blockade, the Union Navy stationed some of its most powerful warships in the roadstead.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] There, they were under the shelter of the shore-based guns of Fort Monroe and the batteries at Hampton and Newport News and out of the range of the guns at Sewell's Point and Craney Island.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] For most of the first year of the war, the Confederacy could do little to oppose or dislodge them.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] When steam propulsion began to be applied to warships, naval constructors renewed their interest in armor for their vessels.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Experiments had been tried with armor during the Crimean War (1853–1856), just prior to the American Civil War, and the British and French navies had each built armored ships and were planning to build others.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1860 the French Navy commissioned *La Gloire*, the world's first ocean-going ironclad warship.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Great Britain followed a year later with HMS *Warrior*, the world's first armor-plated iron-hulled warship.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of armor remained controversial, however, and the United States Navy was generally reluctant to embrace the new technology.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] When the Civil War broke out in 1861, Confederate Secretary of the Navy Stephen R.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory was an early enthusiast for the advantages of armor.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] As he looked upon it, the Confederacy could not match the industrial North in numbers of ships at sea, so they would have to compete by building vessels that individually outclassed those of the Union.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory gathered about himself a group of men who could put his vision into practice, among them John M.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] When Mallory's men searched the South for factories that could build engines to drive the heavy ships that he wanted, they found no place to do it immediately.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the best facility, the Tredegar Iron Works in Richmond, building engines from scratch would take at least a year.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Upon learning this, Williamson suggested taking the engines from the hulk of *Merrimack*, recently raised from the bed of the Elizabeth River.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] His colleagues promptly accepted his suggestion and expanded it, proposing that the design of their projected ironclad be adapted to the hull.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Porter produced the revised plans, which were submitted to Mallory for approval.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] On July 11, 1861, the new design was accepted, and work began almost immediately.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The burned-out hull was towed into the graving dock that the Union Navy had failed to destroy.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the subsequent conversion process, the plans developed further, incorporating an iron ram fitted to the prow.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The re-modeled ship's offense, in addition to the ram, consisted of 10 guns: six 9 in (230 mm) smooth-bore Dahlgrens, two 6.4 in (160 mm) and two 7 in (180 mm) Brooke rifles.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Trials showed that these rifles firing solid shot would pierce up to eight inches of armor plating.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Tredegar Iron works could produce both solid shot and shell, and since it was believed that *Virginia* would face only wooden ships, she was given only the explosive shell.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor plating, originally meant to be 1 in (25 mm) thick, was replaced by double plates, each 2 in (51 mm) thick, backed by 24 in (61 cm) of iron and pine.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor was pierced for 14 gunports: four on each broadside, three forward, and three aft.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revisions, together with the usual problems associated with the transportation system of the South, resulted in delays that pushed out the launch date until February 3, 1862, and she was not commissioned until February 17, bearing the name CSS *Virginia*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Intelligence that the Confederates were working to develop an ironclad caused consternation for the Union, but Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles waited for Congress to meet to request permission to consider building armored vessels; Congress gave this permission on August 3, 1861.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles appointed a commission, which became known as the Ironclad Board, of three senior naval officers to choose among the designs that were submitted for consideration.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The three men were Captains Joseph Smith, Hiram Paulding, and Commander Charles Henry Davis.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The board considered seventeen designs, and chose to support three.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first of the three to be completed, even though she was by far the most radical in design, was Swedish engineer and inventor John Ericsson's USS *Monitor*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson's *Monitor*, which was built at Ericsson's yard on the East River in Greenpoint, Brooklyn, incorporated new and striking design features, the most significant of which were her armor and armament.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Instead of the large numbers of guns of rather small bore that had characterized warships in the past, Ericsson opted for only two guns of large caliber; he wanted to use 15 in (380 mm) guns, but had to settle for 11 in (280 mm) Dahlgren guns when the larger size were unavailable.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] These were mounted in a cylindrical turret, 20 ft (6.1 m) in diameter, 9 ft (2.7 m) high, covered with iron 8 in (200 mm) thick.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The whole rotated on a central spindle, and was moved by a steam engine that could be controlled by one man.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson was afraid that using the full 30 pounds of black powder to fire the huge cannon would raise the risk of an explosion in the turret.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] He demanded that a charge of 15 pounds be used to lessen this possibility.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] As with *Virginia*, trials found that a full charge would pierce armor plate, a finding that would have affected the outcome of the battle.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] A serious flaw in the design was the pilot house from which the ship would be conned, a small structure forward of the turret on the main deck.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Its presence meant that the guns could not fire directly forward, and it was isolated from other activities on the ship.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the late start and the novelty of construction, *Monitor* was actually completed a few days before her counterpart *Virginia*, but the Confederates activated *Virginia* first.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate chain of command was anomalous.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones had directed much of the conversion of *Merrimack* to *Virginia*, and he was disappointed when he was not named her captain.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones was retained aboard *Virginia*, but only as her executive officer.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ordinarily, the ship would have been led by a captain of the Confederate States Navy, to be determined by the rigid seniority system that was in place.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Secretary Mallory wanted the aggressive Franklin Buchanan, but at least two other captains had greater seniority and had applied for the post.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory evaded the issue by appointing Buchanan, head of the Office of Orders and Detail, flag officer in charge of the defenses of Norfolk and the James River.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] As such, he could control the movements of *Virginia*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Technically, therefore, the ship went into the battle without a captain.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the Union side, command of the North Atlantic Blockading Squadron was held by Flag Officer Louis M.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had devised a plan for his frigates to engage *Virginia*, hoping to trap her in their crossfire.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the event, his plan broke down completely when four of the ships ran aground (one of them intentionally) in the confined waters of the roadstead.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the day of battle, Goldsborough was absent with the ships cooperating with the Burnside Expedition in North Carolina.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] In his absence, leadership fell to his second in command, Captain John Marston of USS *Roanoke*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] As *Roanoke* was one of the ships that ran aground, Marston was unable to materially influence the battle, and his participation is often disregarded.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Most accounts emphasize the contribution of the captain of *Monitor*, John L.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Marston did, however, disregard orders from Secretary of War Gideon Welles to send the *Monitor* back to Washington, D.C., ahead of the battle, ensuring that it would be present to confront the *Merrimack*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle began when the large and unwieldy CSS *Virginia* steamed into Hampton Roads on the morning of March 8, 1862.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan intended to attack as soon as possible.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* was accompanied from her moorings on the Elizabeth River by *Raleigh* and *Beaufort*, and was joined at Hampton Roads by the James River Squadron, *Patrick Henry*, *Jamestown*, and *Teaser*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] When they were passing the Union batteries at Newport News, *Patrick Henry* was temporarily disabled by a shot in her boiler that killed four of her crew.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] After repairs, she returned and rejoined the others.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] At this time, the Union Navy had five warships in the roadstead, in addition to several support vessels.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The sloop-of-war *Cumberland* and frigate *Congress* were anchored in the channel near Newport News.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and the steam frigates *Roanoke* and *Minnesota* were near Fort Monroe, along with the storeship *Brandywine*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The latter three got under way as soon as they saw *Virginia* approaching, but all soon ran aground.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and *Roanoke* took no further important part in the battle.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ramming *Cumberland* nearly resulted in the sinking of *Virginia* as well.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia*'s bow ram got stuck in the enemy ship's hull, and as *Cumberland* listed and began to go down, she almost pulled *Virginia* under with her.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the time the vessels were locked, one of *Cumberland's* anchors was hanging directly above the foredeck of *Virginia*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Had it come loose, the two ships might have gone down together.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* broke free, however, her ram breaking off as she backed away.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Buchanan next turned *Virginia* on *Congress*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Seeing what had happened to *Cumberland*, Lieutenant Joseph B.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Smith, captain of *Congress*, ordered his ship grounded in shallow water.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] By this time, the James River Squadron, commanded by John Randolph Tucker, had arrived and joined *Virginia* in the attack on *Congress*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] After an hour of unequal combat, the badly damaged *Congress* surrendered.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] While the surviving crewmen of *Congress* were being ferried off the ship, a Union battery on the north shore opened fire on *Virginia*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] In retaliation, Buchanan ordered *Congress* fired upon with hot shot, cannonballs heated red-hot.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Congress* caught fire and burned throughout the rest of the day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Near midnight, the flames reached her magazine and she exploded and sank, stern first.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Personnel losses included 110 killed or missing and presumed drowned.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Another 26 were wounded, of whom ten died within days.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although she had not suffered anything like the damage she had inflicted, *Virginia* was not completely unscathed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shots from *Cumberland*, *Congress*, and Union troops ashore had riddled her smokestack, reducing her already low speed.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her guns were disabled and several armor plates had been loosened.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Two of her crew were killed, and more were wounded.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] One of the wounded was Captain Buchanan, who stood out into the open top of the *Virginia*, thinking it was perfectly safe, which led to him having his left thigh pierced by a rifle shot.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Meanwhile, the James River Squadron had turned its attention to *Minnesota*, which had left Fort Monroe to join in the battle and had run aground.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] After *Virginia* had dealt with the surrender of *Congress*, she joined the James River Squadron despite her damage.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Because of her deep draft and the falling tide, however, *Virginia* was unable to get close enough to be effective, and darkness prevented the rest of the squadron from aiming their guns to any effect.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* left with the expectation of returning the next day and completing the task.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] She retreated into the safety of Confederate-controlled waters off Sewell's Point for the night, but had killed 250 enemy sailors and had lost two.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union had lost two ships and three were aground.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The United States Navy's greatest defeat (which would remain so until World War II) caused panic in Washington.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] As Lincoln's Cabinet met to discuss the disaster, the frightened Secretary of War Edwin Stanton told the others that *Virginia* might attack East coast cities, and even shell the White House before the meeting ended.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles assured his colleagues that they were safe as the ship could not traverse the Potomac River.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] He added that the Union also had an ironclad, and that it was heading to meet *Virginia*.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Both sides used the respite to prepare for the next day.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* put her wounded ashore and underwent temporary repairs.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan was among the wounded, so command on the second day fell to his executive officer, Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones proved to be no less aggressive than the man he replaced.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] While *Virginia* was being prepared for renewal of the battle, and while *Congress* was still ablaze, *Monitor*, commanded by Lieutenant John L.
[src:battle-of-hampton-roads/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Union ironclad had been rushed to Hampton Roads in hopes of protecting the Union fleet and preventing *Virginia* from threatening Union cities.
